INSERT INTO public.quiz_questions (level_id, topic_tag, question, options, correct_index, explanation)
VALUES
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target reports 30 days payable (DPO), 45 days receivable (DSO), and 60 days of inventory (DIO). What is its cash conversion cycle?', '["135 days — the sum of all working capital days","75 days — receivables plus inventory minus payables","45 days — equal to the days sales outstanding","15 days — the difference between payable and receivable days"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Cash Conversion Cycle = DSO + DIO – DPO = 45 + 60 – 30 = 75 days. This measures how long cash is tied up in operations between paying suppliers and collecting from customers. A negative CCC (some subscription businesses achieve this) means the business operates on other people''s cash; a high positive CCC means the business needs significant working capital investment to grow.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A manufacturing target carries 75 days of inventory, significantly above the industry average of 40 days. What risk does this create for a PE buyer?', '["None — higher inventory is always beneficial for operations","Excess working capital tied up, potential obsolescence risk, and cash-flow drag that can impair debt service capacity","Reduced revenue visibility for customers","Increased tax liability on the acquired inventory"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Inventory at 75 days vs 40 days industry means approximately €X million of excess cash tied up in stock. For a PE buyer, this creates multiple concerns: capital inefficiency (cash trapped rather than available for debt service), obsolescence risk (slow-moving stock may need write-downs), and operational signals (weak sales or production over-planning). Working capital optimisation is often an early value creation lever.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target company has €40M EBITDA, €15M capex, €4M working capital increase, and cash taxes of €6M. What is the approximate free cash flow?', '["€40M — FCF equals EBITDA","€15M — FCF equals EBITDA minus capex, minus working capital change, minus cash taxes","€25M — FCF excludes working capital changes","€55M — add all items together"]'::jsonb, 1, 'FCF = EBITDA – Capex – Change in Working Capital – Cash Taxes = €40M – €15M – €4M – €6M = €15M. This is the cash generated after investments and taxes — available for debt service, distributions, or reinvestment. The 38% FCF conversion (€15M / €40M) is relatively weak; PE-suitable businesses typically achieve 50-70%. The gap between EBITDA and FCF reveals the real economic picture: headline earnings often overstate actual cash generation.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE buyer reviewing a target''s capex notices that €3M is labelled ''maintenance'' and €7M ''growth'' out of €10M total. Why does this distinction matter?', '["It''s just accounting terminology with no impact","Maintenance capex preserves current EBITDA; growth capex generates future returns but reduces current FCF — understanding the mix affects both valuation and the debt serviceability analysis","Only maintenance capex affects financial analysis","Both categories reduce EBITDA equally"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Maintenance capex is required to sustain current operations (replacement of worn equipment, routine facility upgrades). Growth capex funds expansion (new facilities, additional capacity). The distinction matters because: (1) Maintenance is non-discretionary and must continue; (2) Growth is discretionary and can be adjusted; (3) For LBO serviceability, the company must cover maintenance capex after interest — growth capex can theoretically pause during distress. ''Owner earnings'' or ''free cash flow after maintenance capex'' is a common alternative measure.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'The cash flow statement''s operating activities section typically starts with which figure when using the indirect method?', '["Revenue","Net income, adjusted for non-cash items (D&A, SBC) and changes in working capital","Total assets","Closing cash balance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The indirect method begins with net income and reconciles to operating cash flow through: (1) Adding back non-cash charges (depreciation, amortisation, stock-based compensation, impairments); (2) Subtracting non-cash income (gains on asset sales, equity income from associates); (3) Adjusting for working capital changes (AR increase = cash use; AP increase = cash source). This reconciliation exposes the link between accrual-based earnings and actual cash generation. The direct method lists cash receipts and payments by type; it''s less common.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE buyer reviews a retailer''s cash flow statement showing operating cash flow of €25M against net income of €30M. What working capital dynamics might explain this?', '["Inventory has decreased, freeing up cash","Receivables are growing (customer sales outpacing collections) or inventory is building, consuming cash; a €5M working capital use reduces cash flow below net income despite the non-cash add-backs","Tax payments are unusual","The company is issuing new debt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Operating cash flow below net income typically signals working capital growth consuming cash. If the company added back €10M of D&A but operating cash flow is €25M on €30M net income, working capital consumed about €15M. Common causes: rising AR (customer collections lagging), inventory build (production exceeding sales), and other timing differences. In growing businesses, working capital consumption is normal. Concerning when AR growth significantly outpaces revenue growth — suggesting revenue recognition or collection deterioration.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A distressed retailer accelerates collections and stretches supplier payments to boost cash. How does this affect the working capital analysis in diligence?', '["Nothing — working capital is always reported fairly","Pre-sale working capital manipulation (accelerating AR collection, stretching AP, reducing inventory) inflates cash and distorts the ''normal'' working capital position; PE diligence must normalise to historical patterns or industry benchmarks","Inflated working capital benefits the buyer","Working capital cannot be manipulated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pre-sale working capital manipulation is a classic seller tactic: accelerating AR collection (offering discounts or aggressive dunning), stretching AP (delaying supplier payments), or reducing inventory (running it down without restocking). This temporarily boosts cash position but leaves the business with an abnormal working capital base. PE buyers protect against this through SPA working capital adjustments and normalisation to a multi-period average — ensuring the buyer pays for a business with normal working capital, not an artificially depleted one.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target''s DSO (days sales outstanding) is 50 days on €300M of annual revenue. What is the implied accounts receivable balance?', '["€41M — (50/365) × €300M","€50M — DSO multiplied by 1M","€15M — revenue divided by DSO","€150M — half of revenue"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Accounts Receivable = (DSO / 365) × Revenue = (50 / 365) × €300M = €41.1M. This calculation shows how many euros of revenue are tied up in collections. A DSO of 50 days means customers take 50 days to pay on average. For PE analysis: (1) Lower DSO = better cash efficiency; (2) Rising DSO suggests payment issues or relaxed credit policy; (3) DSO stability matters for working capital predictability. Benchmarking against industry peers reveals whether the company has tight collections or is operationally weak.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A company''s inventory turnover is 6x per year. What does this metric measure, and what does a value of 6 suggest?', '["Inventory is counted 6 times per year","Inventory turns (COGS ÷ average inventory) = 6 means the company cycles through its inventory 6 times per year (approximately 60 days of inventory) — moderate efficiency; higher turns indicate faster movement","The company has 6 different product lines","Inventory has appreciated 6x"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Inventory turnover = COGS / Average Inventory. A turnover of 6 means inventory cycles 6 times yearly (60 days average, since 365/6 ≈ 60). Higher turns suggest efficient inventory management (lower working capital tied up); lower turns may indicate slow-moving stock or overstocking. Benchmarking: retailers 5-15 turns; industrial 4-8; high-end manufacturing 2-4. Declining turnover is a warning sign — either demand is weakening or the company is accumulating inventory inefficiently. Strong PE targets maintain or improve turnover.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE target has DSO of 50 days, DPO of 35 days, DIO of 85 days. Calculate the cash conversion cycle and interpret.', '["170 days — moderate for a manufacturer","100 days — DSO + DIO – DPO = 50 + 85 – 35 = 100 days; significant working capital investment required","35 days — equal to DPO","0 days — balanced"]'::jsonb, 1, 'CCC = DSO + DIO – DPO = 50 + 85 – 35 = 100 days. This means cash is tied up for 100 days from paying suppliers to collecting from customers. For each €1 of COGS, 100 days of capital is invested. In revenue terms, CCC of 100 days on €300M annual COGS equals approximately €82M of working capital tied up. Reducing CCC by 10 days releases €8M of cash — a real value creation opportunity. PE firms often target CCC reduction through: faster collections (DSO), supplier negotiation (DPO), inventory optimisation (DIO).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A company reports €100M revenue and €25M Net Working Capital. What is the working capital intensity?', '["25% — working capital as a percentage of revenue","4% — revenue per working capital euro","75% — the inverse","Cannot be calculated"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Working Capital Intensity = NWC / Revenue = €25M / €100M = 25%. This means the company invests €0.25 of working capital for every €1 of revenue. Higher intensity (e.g., 30%+) means more cash is tied up to support operations; lower intensity (e.g., 10%) is more capital-efficient. Services and subscription businesses often operate at low working capital intensity; manufacturing and distribution at higher. Growth drives working capital growth — a company doubling revenue typically needs approximately double the working capital. This is a key cash consumption during growth.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A growing company with 20% revenue growth and 25% working capital intensity will consume approximately how much working capital for each €1M of revenue growth?', '["€0.05M","€0.25M — working capital grows with revenue at the intensity ratio","€1M","€4M"]'::jsonb, 1, 'If working capital intensity is 25%, each €1M of revenue growth requires €0.25M of additional working capital. For a company growing from €100M to €120M (€20M growth): €20M × 25% = €5M working capital consumption. This drags free cash flow and is a real cost of growth often missed in headline EBITDA analysis. In LBO modelling, working capital consumption is subtracted from EBITDA to arrive at FCF for debt paydown. High-growth businesses with high working capital intensity have particularly challenging cash dynamics.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A seasonal business has working capital that swings from €20M in Q1 to €45M in Q3. How should a PE buyer analyse this pattern?', '["Use the peak (€45M) for acquisition pricing","Understand the seasonality (typically revenue concentration patterns), use a normalised average for purchase price, and ensure closing adjustments protect against seasonal manipulation","Use only the lowest point","Ignore seasonality entirely"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Seasonal working capital is common — retailers, agricultural businesses, tourism. Analysis requires: (1) Understanding the seasonality pattern (usually revenue concentration drives the peak); (2) Computing a normalised average across the cycle; (3) Ensuring the SPA''s ''normalised working capital'' closes at a level consistent with the position — not artificially depressed or elevated. A business that has historically averaged €30M working capital should close near this level; the seasonality doesn''t change the fair transaction value.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target''s 3-year average capex is €15M, but the latest year shows €8M. What might this suggest to a PE buyer?', '["The company is becoming more efficient","Potential deferred maintenance: the company may have reduced capex in the pre-sale year to boost reported cash flow and EBITDA, creating a hidden obligation for the buyer who may need to catch up investment","This pattern is always positive","Nothing — capex fluctuates normally"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pre-sale capex reduction is a common seller tactic. Reducing maintenance capex temporarily boosts reported cash flow and may improve adjusted EBITDA (if some capex appears as operating expense). However, the deferred investment creates future obligations: either catch-up capex post-acquisition or declining business performance. PE diligence analyses capex patterns over 3-5 years and separates maintenance from growth. An €8M recent year vs €15M historical average likely means €7M of maintenance has been deferred.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A business is described as ''capital-intensive'' with capex at 10% of revenue vs industry average of 4%. What implications does this have for LBO suitability?', '["Capital intensity is always preferred","High capex consumes cash that could otherwise service debt; 10% vs 4% means 6 percentage points of revenue being redirected to capex, reducing FCF available for debt paydown and constraining achievable leverage","Capital intensity doesn''t affect LBO suitability","It''s always a positive attribute"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Capital intensity directly reduces FCF. A €200M revenue business with 10% capex consumes €20M per year for capex; at 4% it would consume €8M — a €12M difference per year. Over 5 years, that''s €60M less available for debt paydown. This significantly affects: (1) Leverage capacity (lower for capital-intensive); (2) Return generation (slower deleveraging); (3) LBO suitability. Capital-intensive businesses can still be PE targets but require adjusted leverage, longer holds, or operational improvements to justify the investment.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A company''s operating cash flow is €80M, while its reported net income is €30M and depreciation is €40M. What implications does this have for cash flow quality?', '["Cash flow is artificially inflated","Strong cash flow quality: Net income of €30M + D&A of €40M = €70M expected operating cash flow; actual of €80M means working capital released €10M, reinforcing strong cash generation","The numbers are inconsistent","Cash flow is weaker than earnings"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The cash flow bridge: Net Income + D&A + Working Capital Changes = Operating Cash Flow. €30M + €40M + €10M = €80M. This suggests strong cash flow quality — earnings convert to cash plus favorable working capital. This pattern indicates: (1) Real profitability (not just accounting); (2) Strong collection and inventory management; (3) Predictable cash generation. Reverse patterns (operating cash flow materially below net income + D&A) are concerning and warrant investigation of working capital dynamics.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm is evaluating ''Unlevered Free Cash Flow'' versus ''Levered Free Cash Flow.'' What''s the distinction?', '["They are identical measures","Unlevered FCF is cash flow before debt service (used for EV-based valuation); Levered FCF is after debt service (used for equity returns and dividend capacity)","Unlevered FCF is always larger","The two are unrelated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unlevered FCF = EBITDA – Capex – Working Capital Change – Cash Taxes (before interest). This is cash available to all capital providers and is used for enterprise value valuation. Levered FCF = Unlevered FCF – Cash Interest – Mandatory Amortisation. This is cash available to equity holders for distributions or further debt paydown. The distinction matters for: (1) Valuation (EV uses unlevered); (2) Debt capacity analysis (levered shows serviceability); (3) Dividend recap sizing (levered shows extraction capacity).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm analyses ''FCF yield'' for target selection. If a target has €50M FCF and €400M enterprise value, what is the FCF yield and how does this inform decisions?', '["12.5% — a measure of cash generation efficiency relative to enterprise value","25% — double the calculated ratio","€50M — the absolute FCF","Cannot be calculated"]'::jsonb, 0, 'FCF Yield = FCF / Enterprise Value = €50M / €400M = 12.5%. This is the inverse of EV/FCF (which would be 8x here). FCF yield provides: (1) Cash generation per euro of investment; (2) Debt capacity indicator (lenders typically support debt up to 70-80% of unlevered FCF through interest cover tests); (3) Valuation sanity check against EBITDA-based multiples; (4) Return visibility. A 12.5% FCF yield is attractive vs cost of debt — the target generates enough cash to service debt AND grow.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target''s ''EBITDA-to-FCF conversion'' is 75%. What does this measure, and how does it compare to typical PE targets?', '["FCF is 75% of EBITDA, after deducting capex, taxes, and working capital — a strong conversion rate","FCF exceeds EBITDA by 75%","Only 25% of EBITDA converts to cash","The metric is meaningless"]'::jsonb, 0, 'FCF Conversion = FCF / EBITDA = 75%. This means €0.75 of every EBITDA euro converts to free cash flow. Strong performers: 70-85% (indicates efficient working capital, modest capex, sustainable operations). Weak performers: below 60% (capital-intensive, high working capital, or one-time charges). For PE analysis: (1) High conversion validates LBO suitability; (2) Low conversion warrants investigation; (3) Improving conversion over time is a value creation signal. Targets <60% conversion may require adjusted leverage or different value creation thesis.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'An industrial target shows €40M operating cash flow, €45M capex, and no working capital change. Free cash flow is:', '["€0 — operating cash flow equals capex","Negative €5M — capex exceeds operating cash flow","€85M — the sum of both","€45M — equal to capex"]'::jsonb, 1, 'FCF = Operating Cash Flow – Capex = €40M – €45M = -€5M. Negative free cash flow means the business is consuming cash — spending more on capex than it generates operationally. This pattern is: (1) Dangerous for LBO candidates (no cash for debt service); (2) Common in growth/expansion phases (investing in future capacity); (3) A warning signal when combined with weak growth. Negative FCF requires: either the growth justifies the investment (VC/growth equity), or the business needs operational transformation before PE acquisition is viable.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm is testing ''FCF sensitivity'' to input changes. What are the key drivers of FCF that typically receive scrutiny?', '["Only EBITDA matters","Key drivers: (1) EBITDA (largest driver); (2) Working capital changes (% of revenue change); (3) Capex intensity (% of revenue); (4) Cash taxes; (5) Interest costs (for levered FCF); sensitivity analysis tests how FCF changes under adverse scenarios","Only revenue matters","Only capex matters"]'::jsonb, 1, 'FCF sensitivity analysis varies key inputs to understand risk: (1) EBITDA decline (10%, 20%) — biggest single impact on FCF; (2) Working capital intensity changes — if competition forces relaxed terms; (3) Capex requirements — competitive pressure for reinvestment; (4) Tax rate changes — jurisdiction or rate changes; (5) Interest rates — floating rate debt exposure. Running sensitivities identifies where the business is most exposed and validates whether the LBO thesis holds under adverse conditions. Stress testing is a core part of debt sizing.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm''s LBO model uses ''cash taxes'' rather than ''book taxes'' for FCF calculation. Why?', '["Book taxes are not relevant","Cash taxes represent actual cash outflow (what the company pays); book taxes include deferred taxes that don''t create current cash movement; for FCF and debt service analysis, actual cash is what matters","They are identical","Cash taxes are easier to calculate"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Book taxes include both current cash taxes paid and deferred taxes (timing differences between book and tax accounting). For cash flow analysis: only cash taxes reduce available cash. Deferred tax adjustments are non-cash and don''t affect debt service capacity. The difference matters: a company reporting €10M book taxes but paying €7M cash taxes has €3M more FCF than book income suggests. PE modelling uses cash taxes for FCF, debt capacity, and valuation. Accelerated depreciation benefits create deferred tax liabilities but preserve current cash.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A company''s working capital includes trade receivables (€20M), inventory (€30M), and trade payables (€15M). What is the Net Working Capital?', '["€65M — sum of all","€35M — current assets minus current liabilities related to operations = €20M + €30M – €15M","€5M — receivables minus payables","€50M — excluding payables"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Net Working Capital = Operating Current Assets – Operating Current Liabilities = (AR + Inventory) – AP = (€20M + €30M) – €15M = €35M. This is operational working capital, excluding cash and short-term debt. NWC represents capital tied up in operations to generate revenue. Changes in NWC appear in operating cash flow: an increase uses cash; a decrease generates cash. For PE analysis: (1) Normalised NWC sets SPA adjustment baselines; (2) NWC changes drive cash flow; (3) Improving NWC efficiency is a value creation lever.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target has 40 days sales outstanding (DSO). A PE value creation plan targets reducing DSO to 30 days. What is the cash impact assuming annual revenue of €240M?', '["€0 — DSO reduction doesn''t affect cash","€6.6M — a 10-day DSO reduction releases working capital of (10/365) × €240M","€30M — equal to the new DSO","€6.6M annually in perpetuity"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each day of DSO reduction releases: (1 day / 365) × Revenue = (1/365) × €240M = €658K. A 10-day reduction releases approximately €6.6M of cash (one-time). This cash is permanent once realised. Additional benefit: the reduction continues to benefit future growth. PE firms typically implement: (1) Credit policy tightening; (2) Faster invoicing and reminders; (3) Discounts for early payment; (4) Reviewing customer credit terms. Each day saved generates real value creation through better working capital management.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A software company reports €200M revenue with €10M of working capital. A manufacturer reports €200M revenue with €60M of working capital. Why the difference?', '["The manufacturer is less efficient","Inherent business model difference: software has lower working capital intensity (digital delivery, often prepaid subscriptions); manufacturing requires inventory, receivables, and supply chain financing — fundamentally different capital requirements","The data is incorrect","Manufacturing is always cash-negative"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Working capital intensity varies dramatically by business model: (1) Software/SaaS: 0-10% of revenue (digital delivery, upfront subscriptions); (2) Consulting: 15-25% (high DSO from corporate clients); (3) Distribution: 15-25% (inventory + receivables); (4) Manufacturing: 20-40% (inventory, AR, production cycles); (5) Heavy industrial: 30-50%. This structural difference affects: (1) Cash conversion; (2) Leverage capacity; (3) Growth cash consumption; (4) Valuation multiples. Software businesses support higher multiples partly because of their low working capital intensity.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target claims ''working capital neutral'' — stating that NWC will remain stable despite revenue growth. What questions should a PE buyer ask?', '["None — take the claim at face value","Investigate: (1) What specific mechanisms keep NWC constant during growth? (2) Are customer/supplier terms genuinely stable? (3) Is the claim based on recent single-point data or multi-period trends? (4) Are there one-time effects distorting recent NWC?","Accept the claim if management has high integrity","Assume it''s false automatically"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Claims of ''working capital neutral'' growth deserve scrutiny. Most businesses require working capital to scale with revenue. Exceptions exist (subscription software, some service models) but are rare. Investigation: (1) Is NWC truly flat across multiple periods of growth? (2) What drives the stability — payment terms? inventory turnover improvements? supplier financing? (3) Is the claim based on a single recent data point? (4) Are there one-time events (customer mix shift, unusual collections) making recent data misleading? Genuine WC-neutral growth is a significant competitive advantage.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE target generates €60M EBITDA and €45M FCF. The industry average FCF conversion is 65%. What conclusion can be drawn?', '["The target is underperforming","FCF Conversion = €45M/€60M = 75% — above industry average, suggesting efficient working capital, appropriate capex levels, and genuine cash-generating capacity; a positive signal for LBO suitability","The target has accounting issues","The comparison is meaningless"]'::jsonb, 1, 'FCF Conversion at 75% vs industry 65% is a favorable signal. It suggests: (1) Efficient working capital management; (2) Appropriate (not excessive) capex; (3) Sustainable cash generation; (4) Strong LBO candidate characteristics. PE buyers pay premium multiples for businesses with superior cash conversion because: more debt can be supported, faster deleveraging, higher return potential. Low conversion (below 60%) requires specific operational improvements to justify investment; high conversion validates the LBO thesis.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm''s LBO plan includes a ''Working Capital Optimisation'' initiative targeting €10M of cash release. What are the typical levers?', '["Only cost reductions","(1) DSO reduction through tightened collections, faster invoicing, and credit policy changes; (2) Inventory optimisation through better planning, SKU rationalisation; (3) DPO extension through supplier negotiations; (4) Process improvements in order-to-cash cycle","Only revenue growth","Only capital structure changes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Working capital optimisation levers include: (1) DSO reduction: tighten collections, faster invoicing, reduce credit periods, automate dunning; (2) Inventory reduction: demand forecasting, SKU rationalisation, supplier consignment; (3) DPO extension: negotiate longer payment terms, use supply chain financing; (4) Process optimisation: reduce order-to-cash cycle time, eliminate errors and disputes. Each lever can release millions of euros of trapped cash. The combination typically delivers 5-15% working capital reduction within 12-18 months.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target''s cash flow statement shows ''Capex'' as a large negative in Investing Activities. What distinguishes ''Maintenance Capex'' from ''Growth Capex'' in practice?', '["They are indistinguishable","Maintenance capex sustains current operations (equipment replacement, facility upkeep); Growth capex funds expansion (new facilities, additional capacity, technology investments); the accounting distinction is often based on management judgement","Maintenance is always 50% of total capex","Growth capex is always discretionary"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The distinction is operational rather than strictly accounting-defined: (1) Maintenance capex: Non-discretionary, required to sustain current business (replacing worn equipment, facility upkeep, routine IT refresh). Typically 50-70% of total capex for mature businesses. (2) Growth capex: Discretionary investments for future growth (new facilities, additional capacity, R&D-related equipment, technology platforms). Typically 20-40% for growing businesses. For LBO analysis: maintenance capex is a must; growth capex can be paused in distress. ''Owner earnings'' = FCF after maintenance capex only.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm is evaluating ''D&A as a proxy for maintenance capex.'' What are the limitations of this approach?', '["D&A is always perfect proxy","D&A reflects historical investments spread over useful lives; maintenance capex reflects current replacement costs (inflation-adjusted) and actual investment requirements; D&A can significantly understate or overstate true maintenance needs","D&A is never related to capex","D&A should always be doubled"]'::jsonb, 1, 'D&A-as-maintenance-capex proxy limitations: (1) Inflation: D&A reflects historical asset costs; current replacement costs are higher; (2) Asset life assumptions: accounting lives may not match economic useful lives; (3) Technology obsolescence: older assets (fully depreciated) may need replacement; (4) Growth investments: growth-related D&A inflates total D&A above maintenance needs; (5) Different mix: current asset mix may differ from historical base. For PE analysis: verify maintenance capex through management discussion, industry benchmarking, and bottom-up asset analysis rather than relying on D&A proxy.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target has strong EBITDA growth of 15% but FCF growth of only 2%. What could explain this divergence?', '["Working capital is rising faster than revenue, absorbing the EBITDA growth in cash consumption","The business is underperforming","Accounting methods are changing","All EBITDA growth converts to FCF"]'::jsonb, 0, 'EBITDA growth of 15% vs FCF growth of 2% suggests cash consumption is absorbing the earnings growth. Possible causes: (1) Working capital intensification — receivables or inventory growing disproportionately; (2) Capex increase — growth investments consuming cash; (3) Cash tax increase — if the company''s tax position is changing. For PE analysis: this pattern raises questions about sustainability and value creation. Strong EBITDA without FCF conversion creates LBO serviceability risks. The PE thesis would need to address: is the cash consumption investment for future FCF, or is it structural cash inefficiency?'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm analyses ''Cash Conversion Ratio'' — (EBITDA – Capex) / EBITDA. If EBITDA is €50M and capex is €15M, what is the ratio, and how does this compare to industry norms?', '["70% — a typical range for moderate-capex businesses","30% — below average","100% — fully cash-generative","0% — unsustainable"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Cash Conversion Ratio = (€50M – €15M) / €50M = 70%. Industry norms: (1) Software/SaaS: 85-95% (minimal capex); (2) Services: 80-90% (lower capex intensity); (3) Healthcare: 70-85% (moderate capex); (4) Manufacturing: 55-75% (higher capex); (5) Heavy industrial: 40-60% (very capital-intensive). A 70% cash conversion ratio positions this business at services/moderate manufacturing. For PE analysis: higher ratios support greater leverage and faster returns; lower ratios require longer holds and more operational transformation.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target presents financials showing increasing capex as a percentage of revenue (from 3% to 6% over three years). What might this indicate?', '["The company is becoming more efficient","Possible scenarios: (1) Growth investments (new facility, capacity expansion, technology upgrade) — often positive if generating returns; (2) Maintenance catch-up from prior underinvestment — neutral to negative; (3) Technology/regulatory compliance — required but potentially sustainable; requires deeper analysis to determine which","Capex is always a negative signal","The company has more cash available"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rising capex intensity (3% to 6% of revenue) requires interpretation: (1) Growth investments: new capacity, technology platform, geographic expansion — often positive if ROIC is healthy and returns materialize; (2) Maintenance catch-up: if prior years showed declining capex below industry norms, the increase may be fixing deferred issues; (3) Compliance-driven: environmental regulations, technology mandates — necessary but may not generate returns; (4) Industry shift: entire industry requiring higher investment. PE analysis investigates the drivers and evaluates whether increased investment will generate corresponding EBITDA growth.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm''s LBO model projects cash flow over 5 years. What are the key uncertainties in these projections?', '["Only interest rates","Key uncertainties: (1) EBITDA trajectory (growth, margin); (2) Working capital intensification; (3) Capex requirements (maintenance, growth); (4) Tax rate changes; (5) Interest rate volatility (floating rate debt); (6) Mandatory amortisation; (7) One-time events","Only revenue projections","No uncertainties exist"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LBO cash flow modelling uncertainties: (1) EBITDA: growth projections, margin sustainability, potential downturns; (2) Working capital: intensification with growth, potential deterioration; (3) Capex: maintenance requirements, growth investment needs, compliance; (4) Cash taxes: jurisdictional changes, utilization of losses; (5) Interest: floating rate exposure, refinancing needs; (6) One-time events: acquisitions, divestitures, settlements; (7) Macro factors: recessions, regulatory changes. Sophisticated modelling includes sensitivities for each driver and downside scenarios.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm''s exit analysis shows EV at exit of €600M based on 10x EBITDA. Net debt at exit is €150M, down from €250M at entry. How much of equity value growth came from debt paydown?', '["All of it","€100M — the amount of debt paid down during the hold, translating directly to additional equity value at exit (ceteris paribus)","€200M — double the debt paydown","None"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Debt paydown from €250M to €150M = €100M reduction. At exit, this €100M flows directly to equity value (EV – less debt = more equity). Entry equity: €EV_entry – €250M. Exit equity: €600M – €150M = €450M. If entry EV was €400M (10x €40M EBITDA), entry equity = €400M – €250M = €150M. Exit equity = €450M. Total equity growth = €300M; of this, €100M came from debt paydown, €200M from EBITDA growth + multiple effects. The debt paydown portion is roughly 33% of total equity value creation — consistent with typical PE deal attribution.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE target has historically reported working capital at year-end of €30M. In the year of sale, working capital is €18M. What does this pattern suggest?', '["The company has become more efficient","Likely pre-sale working capital optimisation — seller has accelerated collections, stretched payables, or reduced inventory temporarily to boost cash position before the SPA; buyer must apply normalised working capital adjustment to prevent paying for an artificially depleted position","The data is incorrect","Lower working capital is always better"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A €12M drop in working capital right before sale is highly suspicious. Possible causes: (1) Aggressive AR collection (discounts, pressure); (2) Extended supplier payment terms (stretching); (3) Inventory reduction (not restocking); (4) Customer prepayment acceleration. Post-sale, the business reverts to normal working capital, consuming €12M of cash. PE buyers must: (1) Require normalisation at closing based on historical average; (2) Structure SPA working capital adjustment; (3) Reduce purchase price for the abnormal depletion. Failing to do so effectively transfers €12M of value from buyer to seller.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm''s value creation plan includes a ''Capex Rationalisation'' initiative. What would this typically involve?', '["Eliminating all capex","Reviewing capex decisions with ROIC analysis, eliminating lower-return projects, consolidating vendor relationships, shifting to outsourced solutions where appropriate, improving procurement practices — reducing capex without sacrificing operational capability","Doubling capex spend","Stopping all investments"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Capex rationalisation levers: (1) ROIC analysis — evaluate each project for returns; eliminate low-return investments; (2) Vendor consolidation — procurement savings; (3) Make vs buy decisions — outsource where economical; (4) Technology/cloud alternatives — shift from capex to operational spending where appropriate; (5) Better project management — avoid cost overruns; (6) Deferred maintenance — only acceptable short-term. Well-executed capex rationalisation reduces total capex 10-25% without impairing operational capability, directly improving FCF and EBITDA-to-FCF conversion.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A target reports that its customer base includes three large customers accounting for 45% of revenue. What cash flow concerns does this concentration create?', '["No cash flow concerns exist","Concentration creates multiple risks: (1) Collection risk if a major customer has payment issues; (2) Negotiation leverage against the company on payment terms; (3) Cash flow volatility if customers'' needs fluctuate; (4) Potential DSO spikes during customer issues","Customer concentration reduces working capital","It improves cash collection"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Customer concentration at 45% creates real cash flow risks: (1) Collection risk — if a major customer faces distress, 15%+ of revenue becomes uncertain; (2) Negotiation leverage — large customers can force extended payment terms (raising DSO); (3) Volatility — customer demand fluctuations directly impact cash flow; (4) Single-point-of-failure — loss of a major customer damages the business operationally and financially. PE diligence: (1) Assess each major customer''s financial health; (2) Model downside scenarios; (3) Evaluate mitigation options (diversification, payment protection); (4) Build in risk premiums for concentration.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A subscription software business collects €20M in annual prepaid subscriptions on 1 January. What is the cash flow and working capital effect?', '["€20M of revenue immediately, no cash effect","€20M cash inflow on 1 January increases cash balance; €20M is recorded as deferred revenue (liability) and recognised as revenue ratably over the subscription year — creating negative working capital that acts as a source of financing","€20M is recognised as revenue immediately","No effect until services are delivered"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subscription prepayments create favorable cash dynamics: (1) Cash inflow upfront: €20M collected on day 1; (2) Revenue recognition: ratable over 12 months (€1.67M per month); (3) Deferred revenue liability: decreases monthly as revenue is recognised; (4) Negative working capital contribution: deferred revenue is a non-debt liability funded by customer prepayments. This structure makes subscription businesses cash-flow-strong relative to reported earnings. Companies with growing subscription bases often have cash flow materially exceeding reported EBITDA — a key reason PE pays premium multiples for SaaS businesses.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-cashflow', 'A PE firm is comparing two targets. Target A has stable FCF of €30M annually for 5 years. Target B has FCF of €10M, €45M, €30M, €20M, €40M over 5 years. Both average €29M. Why might the PE firm prefer Target A?', '["Target B is always better","Predictable FCF (Target A) supports higher leverage, easier debt service, reduced covenant risk, and better LP communication; Target B''s volatility creates refinancing risk, covenant stress, and uncertainty even with equivalent average cash flow","The averages are identical, so preference doesn''t matter","Target B is more exciting"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Predictable FCF is more valuable than equivalent volatile FCF for LBO purposes: (1) Leverage capacity: lenders accept more debt against stable cash flows; (2) Interest coverage: predictable cash ensures consistent debt service; (3) Covenant headroom: volatility creates risk of breach in weak years; (4) LP reporting: consistent performance is easier to communicate; (5) Refinancing: stable cash flow positions the company for favorable refinancing. Target B requires: lower leverage (to manage volatility), strong reserves for weak years, and careful covenant structuring — all reducing equity returns despite identical average FCF.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'An LBO''s capital structure includes €300M of Senior Debt at 5%, €100M of Second Lien at 8%, and €50M of Mezzanine at 11% (with 3% PIK). What is the blended cash interest rate on the debt?', '["Approximately 6.1%","Approximately 6.4%","Approximately 7.5%","Approximately 8%"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Cash interest = (€300M × 5%) + (€100M × 8%) + (€50M × 8% cash component) = €15M + €8M + €4M = €27M. Blended cash rate = €27M / €450M total debt = 6.0%. The 3% PIK on mezzanine accrues to principal rather than being paid in cash. Understanding cash vs. total interest cost is critical for cash flow modelling — PIK preserves liquidity in early years but increases debt balance over time.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm is negotiating a Term Loan B (TLB) for its LBO. What are the typical key features of this debt instrument?', '["Amortising over 3 years with bank lenders only","Bullet maturity at 7 years with nominal 1% per year amortisation, syndicated to institutional investors (CLOs, loan mutual funds), senior secured position","Convertible to equity automatically","No security or priority claim"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Term Loan B is the most common leveraged loan instrument: bullet maturity (typically 7 years), minimal amortisation (often 1% per year, 99% at maturity), senior secured, floating rate (e.g., SOFR/EURIBOR + 400-500 bps), and syndicated to institutional investors. This structure maximises borrower cash flow retention during the hold period — most debt is repaid at exit, not during operations. TLB is distinct from Term Loan A (bank-held, more amortising) and high-yield bonds (bond-format, typically subordinated).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE-backed company has €40M EBITDA and €240M of total debt. What is its leverage ratio, and how does this typically compare to mid-market LBO norms?', '["6.0x — aligned with typical mid-market LBO leverage (4-7x)","4.0x — above typical LBO leverage","10.0x — extreme leverage requiring covenant waivers","2.4x — conservative industrial leverage"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Leverage Ratio = Total Debt / EBITDA = €240M / €40M = 6.0x. This is within typical mid-market LBO norms (4-7x for stable businesses). The specific ratio acceptable depends on: business quality (stable recurring = supports higher), industry (defensive = higher; cyclical = lower), market conditions (credit availability), and interest coverage. Leverage above 7x typically requires exceptional business quality; below 5x may signal conservative underwriting or weak credit conditions.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'What are the typical seniority ranks in a levered capital structure from highest to lowest priority?', '["Common equity, preferred equity, senior debt","Senior secured debt, senior unsecured/second lien, subordinated/mezzanine, preferred equity, common equity","Random order with no standard hierarchy","Only senior debt and equity exist"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Priority waterfall (most senior to most junior): (1) Senior secured debt — first lien on assets, lowest risk, lowest rate; (2) Senior unsecured or second lien; (3) Subordinated/mezzanine debt — contractually subordinated, higher rate; (4) Preferred equity — dividend preference but no loan structure; (5) Common equity — residual claim. Each tier bears incrementally more risk and earns higher returns. In distress, recoveries follow this waterfall — senior claims are fully repaid before junior tiers receive anything.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A ''first lien'' debt holder has what specific right compared to ''second lien'' holders?', '["No practical difference between first and second lien","First lien has priority claim on secured collateral — in a liquidation, first lien is repaid in full before second lien receives any collateral proceeds","First lien has lower interest rates because it has less security","Second lien has priority in bankruptcy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'First lien debt has priority claim on specified collateral (typically substantially all the company''s assets). In a liquidation, first lien lenders are repaid in full from collateral proceeds before second lien receives anything from the same collateral. This seniority allows first lien to bear less risk and demand lower interest rates (typically 4-6% over reference rate). Second lien holders take subordinated position, accepting higher rates (6-8% over reference rate) for the incremental risk.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE-backed company with €50M EBITDA pays €20M annual cash interest. What is the Interest Coverage Ratio (ICR), and how is this typically interpreted?', '["0.4x — borderline insolvent","2.5x — moderate coverage; typical LBO minimum is 2.0-2.5x","5.0x — highly conservative coverage","Cannot be determined"]'::jsonb, 1, 'ICR = EBITDA / Interest Expense = €50M / €20M = 2.5x. This means EBITDA is 2.5 times interest obligations, providing margin of safety. Typical LBO minimums are 2.0-2.5x; below 2.0x signals elevated risk. Above 4.0x suggests conservative structure or under-leveraged. ICR complements leverage ratios because it reflects actual debt service burden (which depends on interest rate, not just debt size). A company with 6x leverage and 3x ICR may be safer than one with 4x leverage and 1.8x ICR if rates differ significantly.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A leveraged loan contains a ''maintenance financial covenant'' requiring Net Leverage below 6.0x, tested quarterly. What happens if the ratio exceeds 6.0x?', '["The company is immediately liquidated","Covenant breach triggers a ''default'' event, typically requiring the borrower to negotiate with lenders for a waiver, amendment, or equity cure — the lenders gain significant leverage and may charge fees, raise rates, or impose new conditions","The interest rate automatically decreases","Nothing — covenants are never enforced"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Covenant breaches trigger ''default'' events, giving lenders contractual rights: fee payments, rate increases, restrictive new conditions, and potential acceleration of the debt. In practice, sophisticated PE firms work with lenders to negotiate waivers or amendments — but this is a serious process involving: updated financial projections, explanation of breach causes, remediation plans, and often new costs. The credit facility may also include ''equity cure'' rights allowing the PE sponsor to inject additional equity to remedy the breach.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE-backed company''s credit facility includes both ''financial covenants'' (maintenance tests) and ''incurrence covenants.'' What distinguishes these?', '["They are the same thing","Financial (maintenance) covenants are tested regularly (quarterly); incurrence covenants trigger only upon specific actions (additional debt, dividend payment, major acquisition)","Financial covenants apply to public companies only","Incurrence covenants test financial ratios annually"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Maintenance covenants require ongoing compliance with ratios (leverage, coverage) tested quarterly or monthly regardless of company actions. Incurrence covenants only apply when specific actions occur: adding new debt, paying dividends, making acquisitions, or disposing of assets. ''Cov-lite'' structures use incurrence covenants almost exclusively, giving borrowers more flexibility. Maintenance covenants provide lenders earlier intervention rights but are increasingly absent from large-cap leveraged loans.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm is comparing ''Senior Secured'' debt to ''Senior Unsecured'' debt. What is the practical difference?', '["They are identical","Senior Secured has a specific lien on company assets; Senior Unsecured ranks equal to Senior Secured in the capital structure priority but does not have collateral security — typically commands a higher interest rate reflecting the incremental risk","Senior Unsecured is always senior to Senior Secured","Senior Secured has no interest rate"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Both tiers rank senior in the capital structure, but Secured debt has collateral (specific liens on assets). In liquidation, secured lenders are paid first from collateral proceeds; unsecured claimants compete for remaining assets with other unsecured creditors. Secured typically pays 4-5% over reference rate; unsecured may pay 6-7% reflecting the incremental risk. Most LBOs use secured debt for the senior tranche; unsecured is more common in investment-grade corporate finance.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A ''High Yield Bond'' compared to a ''Leveraged Loan'' has what typical differences?', '["They are the same instrument","Bonds typically have fixed rates (vs. floating for loans), longer bullet maturities (8-10 years vs. 7 years), call protection (prepayment penalties), and incurrence-only covenants (vs. maintenance tests for loans); bonds are securities, loans are lending instruments","High yield bonds have variable rates","Leveraged loans mature in less than a year"]'::jsonb, 1, 'High yield bonds vs. leveraged loans key differences: (1) Rate: bonds are fixed, loans floating; (2) Maturity: bonds 8-10 years, loans 7 years; (3) Amortisation: bonds bullet, loans light amortisation; (4) Call protection: bonds have strong prepayment penalties, loans can be refinanced freely; (5) Covenants: bonds typically incurrence-only, loans may have maintenance; (6) Legal form: bonds are securities, loans are lending instruments. LBO financing typically uses loans for senior and bonds for subordinated tranches.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A company''s credit facility includes a ''cash sweep'' provision. What does this require?', '["All cash on the balance sheet must be swept to shareholders","A percentage of excess cash flow (typically 50-75%) must be used for mandatory debt prepayment rather than retained on the balance sheet or distributed to shareholders","The lender can seize cash at any time","No effect on cash"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Cash sweep provisions require the borrower to apply excess cash flow (above mandatory amortisation and interest) to mandatory debt prepayment. Typical levels: 75% sweep when leverage is high; stepping down to 50%/25%/0% as leverage decreases. This accelerates deleveraging and reduces lender risk. Cash sweeps are standard in most LBO facilities. Sophisticated PE firms negotiate ''leverage-based step-downs'' that reduce the sweep as the company delevers.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'What is the purpose of a ''Revolving Credit Facility'' (RCF) in an LBO financing structure?', '["To fund the initial acquisition","To provide ongoing working capital funding and operational flexibility — the company can draw and repay as cash flow fluctuates, supporting seasonal working capital needs, bolt-on acquisitions, and general corporate flexibility","To replace equity capital","To provide long-term financing for capex"]'::jsonb, 1, 'RCFs provide flexible working capital funding during the hold period. Typically sized at 10-15% of total debt package (e.g., €50M RCF alongside €350M term debt), they allow the company to draw and repay as needs fluctuate. RCFs are typically undrawn at closing (only commitment fees apply) and become active during seasonal peaks or opportunistic investments. They rank senior secured alongside term debt and include covenant protections. RCF availability is a key credit support feature for the business.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A mezzanine debt tranche carries 10% cash interest plus 4% PIK interest. What does ''PIK'' mean?', '["A transaction fee paid upfront","Payment-in-Kind — interest that accrues to principal rather than being paid in cash, compounding the debt balance over time and preserving liquidity in early years","Prepayment penalty","Principal insurance kickback"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PIK (Payment-in-Kind) interest accrues to the principal balance rather than being paid in cash. A €100M mezzanine loan at 10% cash + 4% PIK: cash interest = €10M per year; PIK accrues €4M to principal (Year 2 starts at €104M, generating higher subsequent interest). This preserves liquidity during the hold period but increases the debt balance. PIK features are common in mezzanine and second lien tranches. They''re valuable for cash-constrained businesses or when growth investment requires cash retention.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm is evaluating ''unitranche'' financing versus separate senior and subordinated tranches. What advantage does unitranche offer?', '["It''s always the cheapest option","Unitranche combines senior and subordinated elements into one loan with a single lender, offering simpler execution (one lender, one document, faster closing), flexibility on structure, and predictable pricing — at a blended cost higher than pure senior but lower than layered senior + mezzanine","It eliminates all fees","It''s unregulated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unitranche advantages: (1) Single lender relationship — no inter-creditor complexity; (2) One set of documents — faster closing; (3) Flexibility on structure — customised for specific deal; (4) Predictable pricing at a blended rate (typically 6-8% for mid-market). Trade-offs: higher than pure senior cost (5%) but lower than senior + mezzanine layered (6-7% blended). Unitranche has become the dominant financing structure for European mid-market LBOs. Key providers: Ares, Golub, Antares, Apollo Credit, and other direct lending specialists.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE-backed company has €250M of Term Loan B and €50M of Mezzanine debt. The company''s EBITDA falls unexpectedly and it breaches its leverage covenant. The PE sponsor decides to use an ''Equity Cure.'' What does this involve?', '["Converting all debt to equity","The PE sponsor injects additional equity that is treated as an addition to EBITDA for covenant calculation purposes — effectively ''curing'' the breach through equity capital","Selling portfolio company shares publicly","Refusing to honor the debt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Equity cure provisions allow the PE sponsor to remedy covenant breaches by injecting additional equity that is added to EBITDA for covenant calculation. Example: company breaches 6.0x leverage by €10M of EBITDA shortfall; sponsor injects €10M × 6 = €60M equity to ''cure'' the breach. Cures are typically limited (e.g., 5 times during the loan life), often capped in size, and cannot be used in consecutive periods. They''re a valuable flexibility tool for PE firms but signal underlying operational challenges.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm is evaluating ''Term Loan A'' (TLA) versus ''Term Loan B'' (TLB) for an LBO. What distinguishes these?', '["They are identical","TLA: held by banks, shorter maturity (5-6 years), more amortising (10% per year typical), lower spread; TLB: syndicated to institutional investors, longer bullet (7 years), minimal amortisation (1% per year), higher spread","TLA is always cheaper","TLB is for small businesses only"]'::jsonb, 1, 'TLA vs TLB: (1) Holder: TLA by banks (can''t sell secondarily), TLB syndicated to institutional investors (CLOs, loan funds); (2) Maturity: TLA 5-6 years, TLB 7 years; (3) Amortisation: TLA 10% per year + bullet, TLB 1% per year + bullet; (4) Pricing: TLA lower spread, TLB higher; (5) Covenants: TLA has maintenance, TLB often cov-lite. LBOs typically use TLB because its longer, less-amortising structure preserves cash for PE returns. TLA is more common in corporate banking relationships.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A company has €150M of LBO debt maturing in Year 7 of the PE hold. When is typical refinancing considered?', '["At maturity in Year 7","Typically 1-2 years before maturity to avoid refinancing risk and lock in favorable rates if available; often combined with exit timing (refinance and dividend recap, or refinance to extend hold)","Never refinance","Only after Year 10"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Debt refinancing is typically considered 1-2 years before maturity to avoid being forced into refinancing in unfavorable conditions. PE firms often coincide refinancing with strategic events: dividend recapitalisations (extract equity through new leverage), maturity extensions (continue hold period), rate optimisation (lower rates become available). Approaching maturity forces refinancing; planning gives flexibility. Deal exits also trigger debt refinancing or repayment from sale proceeds.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm considers a ''dividend recapitalisation'' — issuing new debt to fund a dividend to the PE fund. What are the typical considerations?', '["Dividend recaps are always done","Key considerations: (1) Maintain adequate credit metrics post-transaction; (2) Ensure the business can support higher leverage; (3) Lender consent and capacity; (4) Impact on future exit; (5) Signal to LPs; (6) Business performance stability sufficient to justify additional leverage","Dividend recaps require regulatory approval","Only public companies can do dividend recaps"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Dividend recaps extract equity value during the hold by increasing debt to fund shareholder distributions. Done right, they extract 0.3-0.7x of invested equity. Considerations: (1) Post-transaction credit metrics must remain serviceable; (2) Business stability for incremental leverage; (3) Lender capacity and willingness; (4) Impact on later exit (higher debt = lower exit equity); (5) LP perception — excessive recaps can appear like extraction at the expense of future returns. Well-executed recaps enhance LP returns by accelerating distributions; poorly-executed ones destroy value.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A leveraged loan typically prices at ''SOFR + 450 bps'' (basis points). What does this mean?', '["A fixed rate of 4.5%","A floating rate: the current SOFR rate (benchmark borrowing rate) plus 4.50% (450 bps) margin; total rate varies as SOFR changes, exposing the borrower to interest rate volatility","A fixed rate of 4.50%","An equity kicker"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Floating rate loans price at a benchmark (SOFR in US, EURIBOR in Europe) plus a margin. If SOFR is 5.25% and margin is 450 bps, the all-in rate is 9.75%. Rates reset periodically (typically every 1-3 months) as the benchmark changes. This exposes the borrower to interest rate risk: if SOFR rises, debt service costs increase. Sophisticated borrowers may hedge part of this exposure with interest rate swaps or caps. Margin compensates the lender for the credit risk above the benchmark.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm''s debt covenants include ''Net Leverage must not exceed 6.5x at Q1, reducing to 6.0x at Q2, 5.5x at Q3, 5.0x thereafter.'' What is this schedule?', '["Irregular covenant structure","A ''step-down'' covenant schedule — as the company deleverages and the PE plan matures, the covenant threshold tightens, providing lenders with progressively stricter tests; this creates deadline pressure on EBITDA improvement or debt paydown","A growth-based trigger","An unusual and poor structure"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Step-down covenants are standard in LBO credit agreements. Early years allow higher leverage (typically 6.5x at Q1) reflecting the post-acquisition capital structure. Covenants tighten over time (reaching 5.0x by Year 3 or 4) pressuring the borrower to deleverage through EBITDA growth or debt paydown. This structure: (1) Aligns with the LBO plan''s progression; (2) Provides lenders with tightening risk controls; (3) Creates discipline on the PE sponsor to execute the value creation plan. Deviations from the path trigger covenant discussions.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'Collateralised Loan Obligation (CLO) managers are the largest buyers of leveraged loans. What is a CLO?', '["A private equity fund","A structured investment vehicle that pools leveraged loans and issues tranched securities (AAA, AA, A, BBB, BB, equity) to investors with different risk/return preferences; enables institutional capital to fund leveraged lending","A bank branch","A hedge fund strategy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'CLOs pool leveraged loans into a diversified portfolio, then issue securities backed by that portfolio in tranches with different risk/return profiles. Investors: AAA tranche buyers (pension funds, insurance companies) get lowest return but highest priority on cash flows; equity tranche (specialised credit funds) gets highest return but first loss position. CLO managers (Blackstone Credit, Ares, KKR Credit, Apollo, CIFC) actively manage the underlying loan portfolio. CLOs are the largest buyers of leveraged loans (~70% of new issuance), making them the critical funding pool for LBO debt.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE-backed company''s senior debt matures in 3 years, and refinancing is needed. What factors affect refinancing terms?', '["Only interest rates","Multiple factors: (1) Current credit market conditions; (2) Business performance since original deal; (3) Remaining hold period and exit timing; (4) Credit metrics (leverage, coverage); (5) Sector sentiment; (6) Lender competition; (7) New deal structure needs (bolt-ons, distributions)","Only the company''s EBITDA","Only the PE firm''s reputation"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Refinancing terms reflect multiple factors, not just absolute interest rates. Business performance (deleveraging achieved) improves terms; sector headwinds worsen them. Market conditions (credit spreads, institutional appetite) matter. Strategic needs: simple refinancing, extend-and-extract dividend recap, or bolt-on financing each favor different structures. Competitive lender dynamics can pressure margins down. Sophisticated PE firms use refinancing windows strategically: extending maturities when markets are favorable, extracting equity through recaps, or simply preserving optionality for exit.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE-backed company has €45M EBITDA and pays €6M capex. Its debt structure includes €160M Senior Debt (at 5%) + €40M Second Lien (at 7.5%). Cash taxes are €5M. What is the Free Cash Flow to Debt Paydown?', '["Approximately €23M","Approximately €28M — EBITDA (€45M) less cash interest (€11M) less cash taxes (€5M) less capex (€6M) plus/minus working capital = approximately €23-25M","€45M — equal to EBITDA","€0M"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Free Cash Flow for Debt Paydown = EBITDA – Cash Interest – Cash Taxes – Capex – Working Capital Change. Cash Interest = (€160M × 5%) + (€40M × 7.5%) = €8M + €3M = €11M. FCF = €45M – €11M – €5M – €6M = €23M (assuming working capital neutral). This is the annual amount available for debt paydown, assuming no reinvestment. Over a 5-year hold, this approximately €100M of cumulative debt reduction capacity (before any further cash generation improvements).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A leveraged loan includes ''call protection'' of 101% for the first 6 months. What does this mean?', '["The borrower can call the debt at any time for 101% of face value","If the borrower prepays the loan (refinances) within the first 6 months, they must pay 101% of face value (1% premium above face) — discouraging early refinancing and compensating lenders for short-dated commitments","There''s no call protection","The borrower can only call after 10 years"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Call protection (or ''soft call'') prevents borrowers from refinancing too quickly. ''101 soft call for 6 months'' means if the loan is prepaid within 6 months, the borrower pays 101% of face value (1% premium). After 6 months, par (100%) prepayment is allowed. Call protection: (1) Protects lenders who committed to the loan; (2) Prevents borrowers from extracting value by refinancing immediately; (3) Typical for leveraged loans (shorter periods) vs. high yield bonds (longer, often non-call for 3-4 years with complex schedules).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm''s LBO analysis includes ''debt sustainability'' testing. What does this involve?', '["Testing if lenders exist","Stress-testing the company''s ability to service and repay debt under adverse scenarios: EBITDA decline, margin compression, working capital deterioration, higher interest rates; ensuring covenants hold and debt remains serviceable in downside cases","Confirming debt is legal","Verifying tax deductibility"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Debt sustainability testing assesses resilience under stress: (1) 10-20% EBITDA decline — does ICR hold at 1.5x?; (2) Margin compression — can the business continue to delever?; (3) Working capital stress — does cash suffice for interest/amortisation?; (4) Interest rate rises — impact on floating rate debt; (5) Covenant headroom in each scenario. A capital structure that holds in base case but breaks in moderate downside is fragile. Sophisticated PE firms size debt based on stress tests, not just base case projections.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm''s senior debt has a ''delayed draw'' feature for bolt-on acquisitions. What is this?', '["The loan is delayed by 6 months","The borrower commits to a total facility size at closing but can draw down portions over a specified future period (typically 12-24 months) for specific bolt-on acquisitions; saves the cost of re-underwriting for each acquisition","A form of interest rate hedge","A regulatory requirement"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Delayed draw facilities provide flexibility for planned acquisitions. The borrower has €150M committed at closing but draws it over 12-24 months as bolt-ons complete. Benefits: (1) Avoids repeated underwriting and documentation for each acquisition; (2) Locks in pricing at closing; (3) Provides acquisition currency for the sponsor. Costs: (1) Commitment fees (0.3-0.5% of undrawn amount); (2) Covenants apply immediately to total committed amount; (3) Lender due diligence at closing on future acquisition pipeline. Common for buy-and-build strategies.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A company''s credit agreement includes a ''Most Favored Nation'' (MFN) clause. What does this typically mean?', '["The borrower receives the lowest interest rate available","If the borrower issues new debt at a wider spread than the existing loan, the existing loan''s margin increases to match — protecting lenders from being disadvantaged by future debt on more favorable terms","The lender is guaranteed to receive the highest rate","Foreign investors receive preferential treatment"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MFN clauses protect existing lenders: if the borrower issues new debt at a spread more than a specified amount (e.g., 50 bps wider), the existing loan''s margin steps up to reduce the gap. This prevents borrowers from issuing new debt that disadvantages existing lenders. MFN has become standard in leveraged loans, particularly cov-lite facilities where incurrence covenants are weaker. MFN ''sunset'' provisions (expiring after 12-24 months) allow borrowers more flexibility after an initial protection period.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm is negotiating with banks vs. direct lenders for an LBO financing. What''s the typical trade-off?', '["Direct lenders always charge more than banks","Direct lenders: higher rates (+100-300 bps) but offer speed, execution certainty, bespoke structuring (unitranche, PIK, bolt-on financing), single-lender simplicity. Banks: lower rates via syndication but slower, less flexibility, tougher terms in adverse markets.","Banks are always more expensive","No meaningful difference exists"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Banks (syndicated loan markets) vs. direct lenders trade-offs: Banks offer lower pricing (better rates via syndication to CLOs and loan funds) but: (1) slower execution; (2) less flexibility; (3) harder to get done in weak markets; (4) multiple lenders can complicate amendments. Direct lenders (Ares, Blackstone Credit, Apollo Credit, Golub) offer: higher pricing (100-300 bps premium) but speed, execution certainty, bespoke structures, single-lender relationships. PE firms choose based on deal priorities — pricing vs. certainty. European mid-market has shifted heavily toward direct lenders.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm''s LBO debt ratios are benchmarked against industry norms. What is typical for a mid-market business services company?', '["0-1x leverage","Leverage: 5-6x EBITDA; Coverage: 2.5-3.5x EBITDA/interest; Senior debt typically 75-85% of total debt stack; cash equity contribution: 30-45% of enterprise value","10x+ leverage always","Leverage varies randomly"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Mid-market business services LBO norms (2024): (1) Leverage: 5.0-6.0x EBITDA for stable recurring services, 4.5-5.5x for project-based; (2) Interest coverage: 2.5-3.5x; (3) Senior debt share: 75-85% of debt stack (typically unitranche or TLB + RCF); (4) Cash equity: 30-45% of EV. Deviations require justification: higher leverage for exceptional recurring revenue; lower for volatile businesses. Benchmarking against recent comparable LBOs provides validation for proposed structure. Sector, size, and conditions create significant variation around these norms.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A company''s credit agreement contains a ''Change of Control'' provision. What does this typically do?', '["Nothing — it''s just legal boilerplate","Triggers default or mandatory prepayment if the PE sponsor sells the company to a new owner — ensuring lenders are protected from deterioration in credit quality or management under new ownership without their consent","Allows the lender to take control of the company","Automatically increases the interest rate"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Change of Control provisions are standard in all credit facilities. Triggered by sale of the portfolio company to a new owner, they typically allow lenders to demand repayment in full (or trigger a put option requiring buyer assumption). Practical effect: debt is typically refinanced at sale, or the buyer negotiates assumption. Change of Control provisions ensure lenders can exit or re-underwrite under new ownership. They''re why exit planning includes debt transition — PE firms manage refinancing alongside transaction processes.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm''s LBO analysis includes a ''Base Case'' and ''Downside Case'' for debt modelling. Why is the downside case critical?', '["It''s just for show","The downside case tests whether the debt structure is viable in adverse conditions — validating covenant headroom, interest coverage, and cash flow sufficiency under stress; failure in the downside case means the deal may not be viable at proposed leverage","Only the base case matters","Downside cases are optional"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Downside case analysis: (1) Stress-tests EBITDA decline scenarios; (2) Validates covenant headroom under stress; (3) Confirms debt serviceability; (4) Tests equity cure needs; (5) Assesses refinancing risk. A debt structure that works in base case but breaks in moderate downside (15-20% EBITDA decline) is fragile. The PE firm should either size less debt, improve business quality, or walk from the deal. Sophisticated underwriters require multiple downside scenarios showing sufficient resilience — not just the base case.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE-backed company reports ''gross debt'' of €300M and ''net debt'' of €240M. What is the likely cause of the €60M difference?', '["Accounting error","Cash and cash equivalents of €60M on the balance sheet — ''gross debt'' is total debt outstanding; ''net debt'' deducts cash that could theoretically be used for repayment","Management bonus accrual","Pension deficit"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Net debt = Gross debt – Cash and Cash Equivalents. The €60M difference is the company''s cash balance. Economic reality: gross debt is total indebtedness; net debt reflects what could theoretically be repaid if all cash were applied. For leverage analysis, net debt is typically used (gives a truer picture of economic debt burden). However, net debt has limitations: not all cash is ''free'' (operating requirements), some cash is trapped (restricted cash, foreign subsidiaries), and cash is volatile. These considerations feed into the EV-to-equity bridge.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm''s debt structure for an LBO can include ''second lien'' or ''junior'' tranches. Under what circumstances are these used?', '["Never used in modern PE","When the senior debt alone is insufficient to fund the deal at the desired equity check — second lien provides additional debt capacity at higher pricing, often 300+ bps over senior; useful for larger deals or more aggressive structures","Only for distressed situations","Only in Europe"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Second lien (or junior capital) fills the gap between what senior lenders will provide and the equity check target. Example: senior offers 5.0x EBITDA of debt but the sponsor targets 6.5x leverage. Junior tranches (mezzanine, second lien, or PIK) fill the 1.5x gap at higher cost (300+ bps over senior). Modern unitranche structures often combine these tiers into one facility. Junior tranches: (1) Reduce equity check; (2) Increase leverage and return amplification; (3) Higher pricing reduces FCF yield; (4) Decrease flexibility in later operational challenges.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm is assessing ''senior debt capacity'' for an LBO. Which factors primarily drive senior debt capacity?', '["Only the equity check size","Primary drivers: (1) EBITDA absolute size (larger = more capacity); (2) EBITDA stability (recurring = more capacity); (3) FCF conversion (cash-generative = more capacity); (4) Asset base (collateral = more capacity); (5) Sector dynamics; (6) Market conditions (credit availability)","Only the CEO''s salary","Only the company''s age"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Senior debt capacity drivers: (1) EBITDA size — larger EBITDA supports more debt; (2) Stability — recurring revenue commands more debt capacity than cyclical; (3) FCF conversion — cash-generative businesses support more debt (same EBITDA); (4) Asset base — tangible assets increase collateral availability; (5) Sector dynamics — defensive sectors higher, cyclical lower; (6) Market conditions — credit availability affects lender willingness. Typical: mid-market stable recurring supports 5-6x senior; cyclical supports 4-5x; highly recurring/predictable may support 6-7x. The combination of these factors sets the ceiling.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm is designing the LBO debt structure. What is the typical optimal split between senior and junior debt?', '["All senior, no junior","Typical mid-market LBO: 75-85% senior debt (including unitranche), 15-25% junior/subordinated — balancing cost (senior cheaper) with debt capacity (junior extends total leverage); structure varies by deal size and conditions","50-50 split always","All junior, no senior"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Typical LBO debt structure: (1) 75-85% senior debt (unitranche or TLB + RCF) — lowest cost, first lien; (2) 15-25% junior debt (mezzanine, second lien, or high yield) — higher cost, extending leverage. Larger deals can support more layered structures (TLB + 2L + HY bonds). Smaller deals often use pure unitranche (one tier). The split reflects: desired total leverage, senior debt capacity, cost optimisation, and market appetite. Structure drives cost — every basis point of junior debt is 2-3x more expensive than senior.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE-backed company''s credit agreement includes ''amendment'' and ''consent'' requirements. What do these enable?', '["They do nothing","The borrower can seek modifications to the credit facility — change rates, extend maturity, amend covenants, sell assets, add debt — requiring specified lender consent thresholds (typically majority, supermajority, or unanimous depending on the action)","They automatically increase interest rates","They eliminate all lender rights"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Credit agreements define amendment/consent requirements: some actions require simple majority (50%), others supermajority (66.67%), others unanimity. Typical: rate changes (simple majority), release of collateral (supermajority), adding new tranches (typically protected by most favored nation and incurrence covenants). Amendments are how companies negotiate flexibility — extending maturity, relaxing covenants, permitting acquisitions. Fees are typically paid to consenting lenders. Sophisticated PE sponsors engage in ''amend and extend'' proactively to improve terms during the hold period.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE-backed company''s Debt/EBITDA declined from 6.5x at Year 1 to 4.2x at Year 4. What likely drove this deleveraging?', '["Only debt paydown","Combination of: EBITDA growth (increasing the denominator) and debt paydown (reducing the numerator) — typical for well-executed LBOs where the company grows earnings while applying cash flow to debt reduction","Only regulatory changes","Only exchange rates"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Deleveraging from 6.5x to 4.2x (2.3x reduction) typically comes from two levers: (1) EBITDA growth — €35M growing to €50M reduces leverage from 6.5x to 4.6x at same debt level; (2) Debt paydown — €50M reduction on €227M original drops leverage by about 1.4x at constant EBITDA. The actual decomposition depends on specific numbers. Understanding deleveraging decomposition matters for attribution: EBITDA growth reflects operational success; debt paydown reflects cash generation and financial discipline. Both together demonstrate a well-executed LBO.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'Debt at a PE-backed company is typically paid in what priority order during operations?', '["Equity first, then debt","Operational priorities first (interest payments, mandatory amortisation, working capital, essential capex), then voluntary debt prepayment/distributions based on covenant flexibility and sponsor decisions","Only first lien, never subordinated","Random order"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Cash flow priority during operations: (1) Essential operations (working capital, capex required to maintain the business, taxes); (2) Interest on all debt tranches (mandatory under covenants); (3) Mandatory amortisation (typically minimal for TLB: 1% per year); (4) Discretionary uses — voluntary debt prepayment (junior tranches first), bolt-ons, or distributions. In distress, this priority changes — senior lenders may force all cash to debt service. Normal operating hierarchy ensures the business operates while debt is serviced.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm considers whether to refinance existing debt 18 months into the hold. What justifies this decision?', '["Refinancing is never justified","Opportunity to: (1) Capture rate improvements if credit markets have tightened; (2) Extract dividends through dividend recap if credit metrics allow; (3) Extend maturities for optionality; (4) Optimise structure for ongoing operational needs","Only regulatory requirements","Only cash flow issues"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Mid-hold refinancing opportunities: (1) Rate reduction — if spreads have tightened since original deal; (2) Dividend recap — extract €X00M of equity through higher leverage; (3) Maturity extension — add 2-3 years of optionality beyond the original maturity; (4) Structural optimisation — replace expensive junior tranches with cheaper senior. Costs: fees, covenant renegotiation, LP disclosure. Decisions involve: hold period remaining, exit planning, market conditions, LP alignment. Well-executed mid-hold refinancings significantly enhance LP returns by optimising capital cost during the hold.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-debt', 'A PE firm''s LBO financing package includes a ''delayed draw term loan'' (DDTL) of €50M available for 18 months. Upon drawdown, what commitment fees typically apply in the undrawn period?', '["No fees apply on undrawn amounts","Commitment fees of approximately 0.3-0.5% per annum on the undrawn balance, compensating lenders for the reserved capacity that cannot be deployed elsewhere","The full interest rate applies on undrawn amounts","Fees are only paid at maturity"]'::jsonb, 1, 'DDTLs (and RCFs) charge commitment fees on undrawn amounts — typically 0.3-0.5% per annum. The lender has reserved capital capacity it cannot deploy elsewhere and charges for this optionality. On a €50M DDTL over 18 months at 0.4%, the cost is approximately €300K before any drawdown. Once drawn, full interest applies. This structure: (1) Provides the borrower with flexibility; (2) Compensates lenders for reserved capacity; (3) Creates cost discipline (borrowers don''t commit to larger facilities than needed).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target generates €50M of EBITDA with a 25% EBITDA margin. Capex is €10M, working capital consumes €3M, and cash taxes are €7M. What is the company''s FCF conversion rate?', '["100% — by definition, EBITDA converts fully to free cash flow","60% — FCF of €30M divided by EBITDA of €50M","75% — because capex should be excluded from the conversion calculation","Cannot be calculated without the interest expense"]'::jsonb, 1, 'FCF = EBITDA – Cash Taxes – Working Capital Change – Capex = €50M – €7M – €3M – €10M = €30M. FCF conversion = €30M / €50M = 60%. A conversion rate below 65% is a yellow flag for LBO suitability because the business generates less usable cash than its EBITDA implies.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A seller presents adjusted EBITDA of €28M, which includes a €3M add-back for ''run-rate savings from a cost reduction programme completed in Q3 last year.'' How should an experienced buyer respond to this add-back?', '["Accept it in full if the programme is documented and the savings appear sustained","Reject it entirely because run-rate adjustments are never legitimate","Accept it in full regardless of documentation — sellers would not fabricate such claims","Reduce the EBITDA by €3M because run-rate adjustments inflate the figure artificially"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Run-rate adjustments are legitimate when a genuine, completed change produces measurable, recurring savings — and the buyer can verify this through documentation and observation of post-implementation performance. They should be rejected when the programme is still in progress, when savings cannot be isolated from other cost movements, or when the assumptions are aspirational rather than achieved.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A software company reports €40M of adjusted EBITDA after adding back €5M of stock-based compensation (SBC). A mature peer in the same sector includes SBC as an operating expense. When comparing EV/EBITDA multiples between these companies, what adjustment should a PE analyst make?', '["No adjustment — SBC is universally treated as a non-cash add-back","Recalculate both companies'' EBITDA consistently, either both including or both excluding SBC","Use the peer''s lower EBITDA because it is more conservative","Average the two EBITDA figures to arrive at a blended metric"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Multiples comparisons require consistent EBITDA definitions. If one company adds back SBC and another does not, the multiples are not directly comparable. The analyst must recalculate one figure to match the other''s convention. The broader debate about whether SBC should be treated as a real economic cost is separate — what matters for comparison is consistency.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'Two businesses both generate €20M EBITDA. Business A has 85% recurring subscription revenue with 8% annual growth. Business B has project-based revenue with 15% annual growth but high volatility. Why might a PE buyer pay a higher EBITDA multiple for Business A?', '["Business A has higher margins than Business B","Business A''s stable, predictable EBITDA supports more debt and generates higher-quality earnings","Business A is in a more attractive industry","Business B''s higher growth rate is less valuable than Business A''s stability"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EBITDA quality — not just EBITDA quantity — drives valuation multiples. Recurring, predictable EBITDA supports higher leverage (lenders accept more debt against stable cash flows), reduces downside risk, and commands a premium multiple. Business B''s higher growth is attractive but offset by earnings volatility that makes it a weaker LBO candidate.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'What does EBITDA stand for, and what is it conceptually measuring?', '["Earnings Before Interest Taxes Depreciation and Amortisation — a proxy for operating cash generation before financing, tax, and non-cash accounting charges","Earnings Before Investment, Treasury, Distribution, and Acquisition","Equity Before Interest Taxes Depreciation and Amortisation — an equity-specific measure","European Based Income Tax Deduction Amount"]'::jsonb, 0, 'EBITDA = Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation, and Amortisation. By removing interest (financing), taxes (jurisdiction), depreciation and amortisation (non-cash accounting charges), EBITDA isolates a company''s underlying operating performance. It serves as a cash-flow proxy because D&A are non-cash, and as a comparability metric because it strips out items that vary due to capital structure and tax regime rather than operational merit.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A company reports EBIT of €22M and D&A of €11M. What is its EBITDA?', '["€11M","€22M","€33M","Cannot be calculated from these two figures"]'::jsonb, 2, 'EBITDA = EBIT + Depreciation + Amortisation = €22M + €11M = €33M. The bridge from EBIT to EBITDA simply adds back D&A, since EBIT is after those non-cash charges while EBITDA is before. This is the standard calculation from the income statement, particularly useful when EBITDA isn''t reported directly — which is common for private mid-market companies.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target reports €40M revenue and €8M EBITDA. A PE analyst compares this to industry peers averaging 25% EBITDA margins. What does this comparison reveal?', '["The target''s margin of 20% is slightly below industry average, potentially indicating opportunity for margin expansion through cost programmes, pricing improvements, or operational efficiency","The target''s margin is above industry average","Margin comparisons are meaningless across companies","The target is unprofitable"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Margin = €8M / €40M = 20%. Against a 25% peer benchmark, the target is underperforming by 5 percentage points — potentially representing €2M of additional EBITDA if brought to peer level. This gap is a common source of PE value creation thesis: identify operational inefficiencies and implement improvement programmes. However, the gap might reflect legitimate structural differences (sector mix, scale, geography) that cannot be closed.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE investor is evaluating ''reported EBITDA'' versus ''adjusted EBITDA.'' What is the primary purpose of adjustments?', '["To hide poor performance from lenders","To normalise EBITDA by removing one-time, non-recurring, or non-operational items to reflect the business''s underlying recurring earning power","To increase EBITDA at every opportunity for valuation purposes","Adjustments are not allowed in PE analysis"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Adjusted EBITDA seeks to answer: ''What is the business''s sustainable, recurring earning power in a normal operating year?'' Legitimate adjustments remove non-recurring costs (one-time litigation, restructuring), owner-specific expenses (above-market compensation), and items unrelated to operations (asset sale gains). But aggressive sellers overreach — treating every awkward cost as ''exceptional.'' The QofE process validates which adjustments are defensible.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target company''s EBITDA add-backs include €1.2M for ''owner-founder''s spouse salary.'' How would a PE buyer typically treat this?', '["Reject entirely because personal expenses cannot be adjusted","Accept if the founder''s spouse is not actively working in the business and will cease being paid post-acquisition; partially accept if the role continues but is overcompensated relative to market","Accept the full amount automatically","Multiply by two to account for the founder''s personal tax benefit"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Owner/related party compensation that exceeds market rates or compensates non-working family members is a legitimate EBITDA adjustment — but only to the extent it will genuinely not continue post-acquisition. If the spouse is a working CFO receiving market compensation, no adjustment is warranted. If the spouse is paid but not working, the full amount can be adjusted. If overpaid for genuine work, only the excess is adjustable. Each adjustment requires verification, not automatic acceptance.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target presents an adjusted EBITDA of €35M with €7M of adjustments (20% uplift from reported EBITDA). A PE buyer''s diligence identifies only €3M of the €7M adjustments as legitimate. What is the ''true'' EBITDA for valuation purposes?', '["€35M — the seller''s figure","€31M — reported €28M plus €3M of accepted adjustments","€28M — the reported figure only","€42M — adding additional buyer-side adjustments"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The valuation EBITDA is: Reported (€28M) + Accepted adjustments (€3M) = €31M. The seller''s €35M figure is aspirational and includes €4M of disputed adjustments. This €4M gap matters enormously at a 10x multiple: it''s €40M of enterprise value. The negotiation often focuses on which specific adjustments are accepted, with the parties agreeing on a figure between the buyer and seller positions.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target company categorises €4M of ''restructuring costs'' in its adjusted EBITDA each year for the past three consecutive years. How should this pattern be interpreted?', '["The €4M is legitimately one-time each year and should be adjusted","Recurring ''restructuring costs'' each year indicate these are part of ongoing business operations, not truly non-recurring items — the adjustment should be rejected","Increase the adjustment to €5M to reflect inflation","Restructuring costs are always adjustable"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The test for a true one-time adjustment is recurrence. An item that appears year after year — even under different labels — is not one-time; it''s part of the business''s normal operating rhythm. Companies may continually restructure, face ''exceptional'' legal costs, or have ''non-recurring'' consulting fees every year. These all fail the recurrence test. Sophisticated QofE analysis tracks line items across 3-5 years to identify patterns.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A ''quality of earnings'' (QofE) report is commissioned during PE diligence. What does it primarily assess?', '["Whether the company has any revenue at all","The sustainability, recurring nature, and accuracy of the target''s reported earnings — including validating adjustments, analysing working capital normalisation, and identifying items that may distort reported EBITDA","The market share of the company","The salary of the CEO"]'::jsonb, 1, 'QofE reports (typically from Big Four accountants or specialist firms like Alvarez & Marsal, FTI) assess earnings sustainability and accuracy. Key focus areas: normalisation adjustments, working capital benchmarks, segment-level EBITDA trends, revenue recognition practices, expense classification, and identification of below-the-line items that may have been inappropriately excluded from operating results. QofE is a critical input to the buyer''s final EBITDA view for valuation and debt sizing.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'Which of the following is MOST commonly a legitimate EBITDA adjustment in mid-market buyout diligence?', '["Ongoing salary costs for essential employees","Annual marketing expenses required to maintain customer base","One-time costs related to successfully implemented facility consolidation with documented cost savings","Regular monthly rent payments"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Facility consolidation — a genuinely one-time event with documented future savings — is a classic legitimate adjustment. The cost was incurred once, the savings continue perpetually, and the financial impact is verifiable. Essential salaries, maintenance marketing, and routine rent are all ongoing operating costs that cannot be removed from EBITDA. The key test: would this cost recur if we ran the business normally next year?'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target reports €3M of ''management bonus accruals'' and excludes them from adjusted EBITDA claiming they relate to the current sale transaction. How should a PE buyer evaluate this?', '["Accept the full €3M adjustment automatically","Examine the bonus plans: transaction-specific bonuses triggered only by sale (change-of-control payments) can be adjusted; ongoing performance-based management compensation cannot","Reject entirely without investigation","Double the adjustment for conservatism"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Transaction bonuses — one-time payments triggered by the sale closing — are legitimate adjustments because they will not recur under new ownership. However, annual performance bonuses based on EBITDA or revenue targets are ongoing compensation that continues post-sale. The diligence team reviews bonus plan documents to distinguish transaction-triggered bonuses from ongoing compensation structures.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target''s adjusted EBITDA includes a €2M add-back for ''recent software implementation costs.'' Upon review, the buyer discovers these costs were for a new ERP system deployed mid-year and will be amortised over 5 years. How should this be treated?', '["Accept as a one-time adjustment because the implementation was a discrete event","Reject the adjustment because software implementation costs are typically capitalised, not expensed — the €2M likely represents implementation labour that would be amortised rather than directly expensed, and ongoing implementations are part of normal business","Accept half the adjustment","Increase the adjustment to €3M"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Major software implementation costs are typically capitalised as part of the software asset and amortised over its useful life. If the €2M flowed through expenses (not capitalised), either the accounting was incorrect or the costs were truly expense-type (training, change management). Mid-market companies continuously implement, upgrade, or replace IT systems — these are part of the ongoing cost base, not one-time adjustments. Each deal requires specific investigation of what the €2M actually represents.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE buyer calculates ''LTM EBITDA'' (Last Twelve Months) for a target being acquired in June 2024. What period does this cover?', '["January 2024 through December 2024","July 2023 through June 2024 — the most recent 12 months of performance","The company''s most recent fiscal year","Any 12-month period chosen by the buyer"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LTM EBITDA = the most recent 12 months of performance ending at the analysis date. For a June 2024 acquisition, LTM covers July 2023–June 2024. LTM is preferred over fiscal year data because it captures the most current performance — especially important if the business has changed significantly since the last fiscal year-end. LTM EBITDA is the standard reference for pricing multiples at the time of transaction.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target was acquired in June 2024 at 10x LTM EBITDA of €30M. A PE buyer also examines ''NTM EBITDA'' (Next Twelve Months). What is the difference and relevance?', '["NTM EBITDA is historical; LTM is projected","NTM EBITDA is forward-looking (next 12 months) and captures expected growth, while LTM is backward-looking — if growth is strong, the deal looks cheaper on NTM than LTM","LTM and NTM are always identical","NTM EBITDA is used only for public companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'NTM (Next Twelve Months) EBITDA reflects projections for the upcoming period. A deal at 10x LTM (€30M) for €300M EV may be 9x NTM if EBITDA grows to €33M. NTM captures the business''s expected trajectory and is particularly relevant when LTM is unrepresentative (e.g., impact of an acquisition, one-time events, cyclical trough). Both LTM and NTM multiples are typically reported for context.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target PE firm''s analysis includes ''pro-forma EBITDA'' incorporating the effect of a recent acquisition completed 8 months before the sale. What is the purpose?', '["To inflate reported earnings artificially","To reflect the combined business as if the acquisition had occurred at the start of the period, providing a clearer picture of the current consolidated performance","To exclude the acquisition entirely","To predict future earnings"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pro-forma EBITDA combines historical results with recent acquisitions or divestitures as if they had occurred earlier in the period. This normalises the comparison and reflects the current business configuration. Without pro-forma adjustment, LTM EBITDA mixes 8 months of standalone performance with 4 months of combined performance — a mix that doesn''t represent what the business looks like going forward. Pro-forma is legitimate when properly computed; aggressive sellers may overreach by including unrealised synergies.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A bolt-on acquisition generating €4M of standalone EBITDA is integrated into a target''s business. The seller claims pro-forma EBITDA including €1M of ''realised synergies.'' How should a PE buyer evaluate this?', '["Accept all synergies without verification","Scrutinise whether the synergies have actually been realised (not projected), are sustainable, and are properly documented; only realised and verifiable synergies belong in EBITDA","Automatically reject any synergy adjustment","Increase the synergies to €2M"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Synergies from acquisitions can be legitimately included in pro-forma EBITDA only if they are: (1) actually realised, not projected; (2) documented with specific cost savings or revenue gains; (3) sustainable into the future. Sellers often stretch to include synergies that are still being captured or that rely on management''s optimistic estimates. QofE analysis distinguishes between achieved synergies (include) and targeted synergies (exclude from historical EBITDA).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target company had a disastrous Q3 with a one-time €3M customer lawsuit settlement. Its reported LTM EBITDA is €20M. What is a potential normalisation approach?', '["Do nothing — the event is already reflected in LTM","Adjust LTM EBITDA upward by €3M to normalise for the one-time settlement, making the underlying business''s earning power more visible","Reduce LTM EBITDA by an additional €3M","Multiply LTM EBITDA by 1.5 to account for the bad quarter"]'::jsonb, 1, 'One-time settlement costs that will not recur can legitimately be added back. Adjusted LTM EBITDA = €20M + €3M = €23M. This gives a clearer picture of underlying earning power. However, the adjustment must satisfy key tests: (1) the lawsuit must be genuinely resolved; (2) similar lawsuits should not be likely in the future; (3) the event is not a symptom of systemic problems (e.g., product safety issues that generate repeat litigation). Otherwise the €3M is not truly non-recurring.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A QofE report identifies that the target''s EBITDA has been inflated by €1.5M from ''below cost-of-capital related party transactions'' (paying the founder''s property company below-market rent). How should this be adjusted?', '["No adjustment needed — the rent payments are factual","EBITDA should be reduced by €1.5M to normalise the rent to market levels, because the below-market rate will not continue post-acquisition when the related party relationship ends or is renegotiated","EBITDA should be increased by €1.5M to show conservative results","The adjustment depends only on the tax treatment"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Related party transactions at below-market rates artificially inflate EBITDA because the company is not bearing market-level costs. Normalisation requires adjusting these to market: if the company pays €500K rent but market rent would be €2M, EBITDA is overstated by €1.5M. Post-acquisition, the PE buyer cannot rely on below-market related party deals — either they end (increasing costs) or are renegotiated. This adjustment is a downward normalisation, not a credit to the seller.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE analyst is evaluating ''segment EBITDA'' for a multi-business target. Which of the following is most important to verify?', '["Total EBITDA equals the sum of segment EBITDA","Corporate overhead and shared costs are properly allocated across segments — some sellers hide overhead at the corporate level, making individual segments appear more profitable than they would be as standalone businesses","Segments have the same EBITDA margins","Segment reporting is optional"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A common tactic: reported segment EBITDA excludes corporate overhead (allocated centrally rather than to segments), making individual segments look more profitable than they really are. If a segment generates €10M standalone EBITDA but would bear €2M of allocated corporate overhead, its ''true'' EBITDA is €8M. This matters for sum-of-the-parts valuation, divestiture decisions, and understanding real business unit performance. Diligent analysis scrutinises overhead allocation methodology.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target''s adjusted EBITDA includes €1.8M labelled ''professional fees for the transaction.'' How should these be treated?', '["Reject the adjustment — transaction costs are operating costs","Accept as a legitimate adjustment — transaction-specific legal, advisory, and accounting fees are one-time and will not recur for the buyer as operating costs","Include in EBITDA and then adjust again","Double the adjustment for conservatism"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Transaction fees (advisory, legal, accounting, due diligence, tax structuring) are genuinely one-time and related to the sale process itself. They will not recur for the buyer in normal operations. Legitimate adjustment. However, the buyer must verify: are these true transaction fees or disguised ordinary expenses? Do they match expected magnitudes for a deal of this size? Are ongoing professional fees (normal legal, accounting for operations) being inadvertently included?'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target''s LTM EBITDA is €40M. The PE buyer''s own QofE-adjusted view lowers it to €35M. At a negotiation multiple of 9x, what is the impact on Enterprise Value?', '["€1M — the difference multiplied by a factor","€45M — the €5M EBITDA difference multiplied by 9x","No impact — the multiple adjusts to compensate","Cannot be determined without knowing net debt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Every €1M of EBITDA adjustment translates to 9x that amount in enterprise value (at a 9x multiple). The €5M EBITDA difference = €45M of EV. This is why QofE is so economically important: a seemingly small €5M disagreement on EBITDA can shift deal value by €45M. Sophisticated sellers push for higher adjustments; sophisticated buyers push back — and the negotiation often settles somewhere between the two QofE views.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE buyer''s internal analysis distinguishes ''cash EBITDA'' from ''accounting EBITDA.'' What is the distinction?', '["They are identical measures","Cash EBITDA excludes non-cash accounting items that remain in accounting EBITDA (stock-based compensation, asset impairments, certain pension costs); it attempts to measure actual cash-generating capacity","Cash EBITDA is always smaller than accounting EBITDA","Cash EBITDA is used only for tax purposes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Cash EBITDA adjusts accounting EBITDA to remove items that are in accounting EBITDA but don''t represent cash generation. Common exclusions: stock-based compensation (if added back), changes in asset valuations, non-cash pension movements. The goal is to approximate actual cash operating generation before financing, capex, and working capital. Different PE firms and analysts use slightly different definitions, so consistency in methodology matters.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE analyst is evaluating EBITDA conversion to free cash flow. A target shows EBITDA of €50M but FCF of only €15M. What is the most likely primary driver of the €35M gap?', '["Accounting errors","Some combination of high capex, working capital growth, significant cash taxes, and potentially higher-than-D&A maintenance investment","Interest expense alone","The EBITDA figure is fabricated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The EBITDA-to-FCF gap (€50M to €15M = 30% conversion) reflects real cash leakage not captured in EBITDA. Common drivers: capex (especially for capital-intensive businesses), working capital investment (for growing companies), cash taxes (not reflected in pre-tax EBITDA), and timing of cash payments. PE buyers must understand which driver explains the gap — addressable drivers (e.g., excess working capital) offer value creation opportunity; structural drivers (e.g., inherent capex intensity) are limits.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'What is a major limitation of using EBITDA as a performance measure?', '["It is too simple to calculate","EBITDA ignores capital expenditure requirements and working capital investments — a capital-intensive business may have strong EBITDA but poor cash generation after reinvestment","EBITDA is always negative","EBITDA cannot be compared across companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EBITDA''s key limitation is that it ignores reinvestment needs. A business with €50M EBITDA but €40M annual capex has only €10M before debt service, taxes, and working capital. A similar business with €50M EBITDA and €10M capex has €40M available. Both look identical on EBITDA but are fundamentally different. This is why ''EBITDA less capex'' (sometimes called ''EBITDA less maintenance capex'' or ''owner earnings'') is a more meaningful measure for capital-intensive businesses.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target company''s LTM EBITDA shows significant quarter-over-quarter volatility. A PE buyer sees €3M, €8M, €7M, and €2M across the four quarters. What should this pattern prompt?', '["Immediate rejection of the deal","Investigation into whether the volatility reflects seasonality (requiring normalised annual view), cyclicality (requiring downside stress testing), or operational instability (potential concern)","Averaging the quarters to get €5M quarterly","Ignoring the volatility as irrelevant"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Quarterly EBITDA volatility can reflect different underlying causes: seasonality (e.g., retail Q4 peak is normal); cyclicality (exposure to economic cycles requires stress testing); or operational instability (inconsistent performance signals underlying problems). The PE buyer must understand which is driving volatility. Seasonal patterns are fine for LBO candidates as long as annual performance is stable. Operational instability is a red flag even if annual totals look acceptable.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target claims €50M of ''adjusted EBITDA'' and states that €15M of adjustments (30% uplift) are justified. A PE analyst''s comparable deals show sellers typically have 10-15% uplift. What does this comparison suggest?', '["The target''s adjustments are in line with industry norms","The unusually large adjustment quantum is a red flag warranting extra scrutiny — when adjustments significantly exceed peer patterns, the risk of aggressive or unjustified items is elevated","Adjustments are unrelated to comparability","The deal should be rejected immediately"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Adjustment quantum is a signal of seller aggressiveness. When a seller''s 30% uplift substantially exceeds typical patterns (10-15%), it suggests inclusion of questionable adjustments. Not every over-standard case involves problems (some businesses have genuinely unusual situations), but it signals the diligence team must be especially careful. Conversely, a seller with minimal adjustments or adjustments below peer average may be signalling transparency and genuine performance.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A manufacturer reports EBITDA that has grown consistently over 5 years. However, its ''EBITDA margin'' has declined from 22% to 17%. What does this reveal?', '["Strong operational performance — EBITDA is growing","Revenue has grown faster than EBITDA, suggesting margin compression — perhaps from pricing pressure, input cost inflation, or mix shift to lower-margin products","The company has fewer customers","EBITDA margin is meaningless"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Growing EBITDA with declining margin means revenue is growing faster than profits — margin is compressing even if absolute EBITDA rises. This pattern often reflects: pricing pressure from competitors; input cost inflation not passed through; growth in lower-margin segments diluting blended margins; or investments in sales/marketing without proportional revenue return. The trend matters more than the absolute: a business with 17% and declining margins is less attractive than one with stable 20% margins, all else equal.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE analyst evaluates the ratio of adjusted EBITDA to reported EBITDA for multiple peers. Company A: 115% (15% uplift). Company B: 120%. Company C: 145%. What does Company C''s ratio suggest?', '["It is the highest quality company","A 45% uplift is highly unusual and suggests either very legitimate one-time items or aggressive adjustments requiring careful scrutiny","All three companies are equivalent","The comparison is meaningless"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A 45% EBITDA uplift is highly unusual. Possible explanations: a truly exceptional period (recent legal settlement, one-time write-off, temporary disruption) genuinely requiring large adjustment, or aggressive seller reframing of recurring costs. The diligence team must determine which. When uplifts exceed 30-40%, the burden of proof on specific adjustments shifts to the seller. Pattern analysis across peer deals helps identify outliers deserving extra scrutiny.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE analyst compares EBITDA margins across three companies in the same industry. Company X: 18%. Company Y: 22%. Company Z: 28%. What is the most valuable interpretation?', '["Company Z has the highest quality; Company X has the lowest","The pattern raises questions about what drives the margin differentials: is Z actually better (higher pricing, lower costs, mix shift), or are Z''s margins inflated by aggressive accounting, unusual benefits, or a fundamentally different business model within the industry","All three companies must have the same margins","Margin comparisons across companies are always misleading"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Margin differences can reflect: genuine operational superiority (better products, scale economics, pricing power, cost discipline); mix differences (different service/product tiers); one-time effects that are not sustainable; or aggressive accounting that won''t continue. Analysis should separate these drivers. A margin-superior company like Company Z might be an ideal acquisition target (if genuine) or a value trap (if accounting-driven). Understanding root causes is essential.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A distressed company reports ''EBITDAR'' — EBITDA plus Rent. In what circumstances is this metric sometimes used?', '["When a company''s rent expense is particularly high","When analysing companies with significant operating lease expenses (retail, restaurants, hotels), EBITDAR allows comparison between companies that own vs. lease their real estate — though this has become less common under IFRS 16 which brings most leases onto the balance sheet","EBITDAR is never used","Only in construction industry analysis"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EBITDAR (EBITDA + Rent) was historically used to compare companies with different property ownership structures — an asset-heavy company that owns its stores has depreciation in its EBITDA while a tenant company has rent in operating expenses. EBITDAR normalises for this. IFRS 16 (effective 2019) brought operating leases onto balance sheets, largely eliminating the distortion by pushing rent-like payments to D&A and interest. EBITDAR is now less common but still used in sectors with heavy real estate operations.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target''s EBITDA includes a non-recurring €4M gain from selling excess land. How should this be treated?', '["Include in EBITDA as a normal revenue event","Remove from EBITDA — asset sale gains are non-operating and will not recur as part of the business''s ongoing earnings, so they should be excluded from the EBITDA used for valuation","Double the amount for conservatism","Include only half"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gains from asset sales (land, excess equipment, business divestitures) are non-operating and typically non-recurring. They belong outside EBITDA for valuation purposes. Similarly, gains from investments, FX hedges, or insurance recoveries are typically excluded. However, be consistent: if gains are excluded, losses from similar non-operating events should also be excluded. The buyer''s EBITDA should reflect ongoing operations only.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A target''s most recent quarter shows record-high EBITDA driven by a €2M reduction in ''warranty accrual.'' What should a PE buyer investigate?', '["Nothing — lower warranty accrual is always positive","Whether the reduction reflects genuine improvement in product quality (reducing expected warranty claims) or is an accounting choice to reduce accruals, artificially boosting reported EBITDA for the sale process","Treat the €2M as pure profit","Increase the accrual by €2M"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Warranty accruals are estimates of future product warranty costs. Reducing accruals requires either improved product quality (justifying lower reserves) or a change in accounting estimate. The timing is critical: reducing accruals right before a sale is a classic seller trick to inflate reported EBITDA. The PE buyer should investigate whether the reduction is justified by operational improvements or represents an aggressive accounting choice. If the former, it''s sustainable; if the latter, it will reverse post-acquisition.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'An industrial target''s EBITDA has grown from €20M to €28M over three years. A PE buyer''s analysis shows that €5M of the €8M growth came from ''currency translation effects'' (favourable FX). How should this be interpreted?', '["The growth is entirely genuine operational improvement","Only €3M of the €8M growth represents underlying business performance; the FX-driven portion is volatile and should not be projected forward without careful analysis of exposure and hedging","FX effects should be doubled in the analysis","FX gains are always equivalent to operational gains"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Currency translation gains for international businesses can significantly boost reported EBITDA without reflecting underlying performance. PE buyers separate ''underlying EBITDA growth'' (currency-neutral) from ''reported EBITDA growth'' to understand genuine operational trajectory. If FX gains reverse in subsequent periods (currencies move the other way), the apparent growth disappears. Constant-currency analysis and FX hedging policy are important elements of diligence for international businesses.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE buyer is comparing two targets with identical €30M LTM EBITDA. Target A has grown EBITDA at 4% annually for five years; Target B has grown at 12% annually over the same period. How does this affect valuation?', '["Both targets should be priced identically","Target B typically commands a higher EBITDA multiple reflecting its stronger growth trajectory — though the buyer must assess whether the growth is sustainable or reflects recent one-time effects","Target A is more attractive because of stability","Growth history has no impact on pricing"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Higher EBITDA growth commands premium multiples because future cash flows grow faster. Target B might trade at 11-12x vs. Target A''s 9-10x — a €30-60M valuation difference on €30M EBITDA. However, the PE buyer must assess growth sustainability: is the 12% growth from structural tailwinds (sustainable), market share gains (sustainable for a while), or one-time events (not sustainable)? Due diligence focuses on understanding the growth drivers and their future trajectory.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE buyer is assessing a target where adjusted EBITDA has not been independently verified. What does a QofE process add beyond accepting management''s adjusted EBITDA?', '["Nothing — management''s figures are accurate","An independent analysis that validates add-backs, identifies adjustments the buyer-side should make (that seller excluded), verifies working capital, and produces a defensible EBITDA for pricing and debt underwriting","Increased legal fees only","Seller-side advocacy for higher valuation"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Independent QofE goes beyond management presentation: it validates adjustments through documentation, identifies buyer-side adjustments that sellers have omitted (e.g., working capital normalisation the seller didn''t include), verifies underlying EBITDA through detailed testing, and produces a buyer-side EBITDA view. This independent figure is what the PE firm uses for pricing, lender underwriting, and IC presentation — separate from the seller''s aspirational number.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE buyer''s final adjusted EBITDA is €42M after all QofE work, while the seller''s is €50M. The buyer offers 9.5x multiple and the seller demands 10x multiple. What are the two ways each side can close the gap?', '["Only one negotiation axis: price","Both sides can either compromise on multiple (e.g., settle at 9.75x) or compromise on adjusted EBITDA (accept buyer-side or seller-side adjustments); real-world negotiations often settle both dimensions in combination","The deal cannot be completed","The seller always wins on both dimensions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In reality, negotiations settle both dimensions. The buyer might accept some seller adjustments (raising the agreed EBITDA toward €46M) while the seller accepts a lower multiple (9.6x). Example: Buyer offers 9.5x × €42M = €399M; seller wants 10x × €50M = €500M. A settled deal at 9.7x × €45M = €437M might bridge the gap. This is why QofE, multiple benchmarking, and negotiation strategy all matter simultaneously — the two dimensions aren''t independent.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-ebitda', 'A PE firm''s LBO model uses €35M of forecasted Year 1 EBITDA for debt sizing at 5.5x leverage. If actual Year 1 EBITDA comes in at €32M instead, what is the implication?', '["No implication — the debt remains the same","The actual leverage ratio rises to approximately 6.0x (€192M debt / €32M EBITDA), bringing the company closer to or potentially breaching covenant thresholds and requiring corrective action","The debt amount adjusts automatically","Leverage ratios don''t depend on actual EBITDA"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Debt is fixed at closing based on underwritten EBITDA. If actual EBITDA underperforms, the leverage ratio (Debt/EBITDA) rises mechanically. Example: €35M × 5.5x = €192.5M debt. If EBITDA falls to €32M, leverage = €192.5M / €32M = 6.0x — a meaningful increase that may approach covenant thresholds. This is why EBITDA accuracy matters so much in deal underwriting: EBITDA errors amplify into leverage and covenant risks.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target has an equity value of €420M, financial debt of €180M, cash of €40M, and an underfunded pension of €25M. What is the enterprise value?', '["€560M — equity plus financial debt minus cash","€585M — equity plus financial debt plus pension deficit minus cash","€640M — the sum of all items","€600M — equity plus financial debt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EV = Equity Value + Net Debt + Debt-Like Items. Here: €420M + (€180M – €40M cash) + €25M pension = €585M. Pension deficits are debt-like items because they represent real economic obligations the buyer inherits. Excluding them understates the true cost of the acquisition and transfers hidden liability to the buyer.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'During SPA negotiation, a seller insists that ''normalised working capital'' at closing be set at €12M, while the buyer''s analysis suggests €18M is the true normalised level. What is the financial implication of this difference?', '["It is a technical dispute with no cash impact","If the seller''s number is accepted, the buyer effectively pays €6M extra at closing","If the seller''s number is accepted, the seller transfers €6M of extra working capital","The difference only matters for tax reporting, not deal economics"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The SPA''s working capital adjustment mechanism reduces the purchase price if actual closing working capital is below the normalised level. If the ''normal'' is set artificially low at €12M (vs. a true €18M), the seller keeps €6M of working capital the buyer will need to fund post-closing. This is why working capital is one of the most contentious areas in deal completion.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE firm acquires a business at an enterprise value of €400M (10x EBITDA of €40M). Over the hold period, EBITDA grows to €55M and €100M of debt is repaid. If the company is sold at the same 10x multiple, what is the equity value at exit, assuming entry debt of €250M?', '["€400M — equity value always equals enterprise value at exit","€400M — 10x multiple applied to €40M EBITDA","€400M — €55M EBITDA x 10 multiple minus €150M remaining debt","€550M — the increase in EBITDA drives exit equity value"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Exit EV = €55M x 10 = €550M. Remaining debt = €250M – €100M = €150M. Exit equity value = €550M – €150M = €400M. Compared to entry equity of €150M (€400M EV – €250M debt), this is a 2.7x MOIC — driven by EBITDA growth (€15M x 10 = €150M) and debt paydown (€100M), even with no multiple expansion.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A buyer is negotiating a deal where the seller proposes pricing the acquisition on equity value rather than enterprise value. Why would a sophisticated PE buyer resist this approach?', '["Equity value is easier to manipulate through accounting adjustments","Enterprise value is capital-structure-neutral and creates a cleaner comparison across deals and multiples","Equity value is only appropriate for distressed transactions","Equity value excludes fixed assets, which are important to the buyer"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Enterprise value treats the business as a whole (debt plus equity claims), making it comparable across companies with different capital structures. Equity value reflects a specific capital structure that will change in the acquisition. Pricing on EV allows the buyer to structure the financing independently of the acquisition price negotiation.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'What does Enterprise Value (EV) conceptually represent?', '["The cash paid by the PE firm at closing","The total value of a business''s operations, representing the sum of all capital provider claims (equity holders, debt holders, other financial stakeholders) — the value before how the business is financed","Only the equity portion of the business","The annual revenue of the company"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Enterprise Value represents the total value of a business''s operations as if acquiring all the claims on it — both equity and debt. EV is capital-structure-neutral: it answers ''what is the business worth?'' independently of how it is financed. A company with €500M EV could have €500M equity and no debt, or €200M equity and €300M debt — the operating business value is the same.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'The fundamental bridge between Enterprise Value and Equity Value can be expressed as:', '["EV = Equity Value + Revenue","Equity Value = EV – Net Debt – Debt-Like Items + Non-Operating Assets","Equity Value = EV + Net Debt","EV = Equity Value × Leverage Ratio"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The EV-to-equity bridge subtracts net debt and debt-like items (pension deficits, certain contingent liabilities, deferred consideration) from EV to arrive at equity value — what the equity holders actually receive. Non-operating assets (surplus cash, non-core investments) are added because they''re not reflected in the operating EV. This bridge is the heart of deal pricing: the buyer pays EV''s equivalent in cash and assumed debt.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A company has €300M of financial debt and €45M of cash. What is its ''net debt''?', '["€345M — the sum of debt and cash","€255M — debt minus cash","€300M — debt only, ignoring cash","€45M — cash only"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Net Debt = Financial Debt – Cash = €300M – €45M = €255M. Net debt represents the economic debt obligation after netting available cash that could theoretically be used for repayment. For pricing purposes, net debt is deducted from EV to reach equity value. However, not all cash is ''free'' — operating cash required to run the business is excluded from the netting calculation.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target''s balance sheet shows €50M of cash. The PE buyer''s diligence reveals €15M is required for day-to-day operations (working capital cash), leaving €35M ''surplus.'' How should cash be treated in the EV-to-equity bridge?', '["All €50M is netted against debt (full netting)","Only the €35M of surplus cash should be netted against debt — the €15M of operating cash is needed to run the business and belongs with operations, not as a debt offset","No cash is netted","Cash is never included in the calculation"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Not all cash is ''free'' — a business requires minimum operating cash (e.g., float in the bank for weekly payroll, customer deposits, reserves). Sophisticated deal pricing distinguishes ''operating cash'' (required for operations) from ''surplus cash'' (excess). Only surplus cash is netted against debt. This prevents sellers from claiming all cash as a debt offset when some is genuinely required to operate. The buyer''s QofE typically defines the operating cash threshold.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'Which of the following would typically be treated as a ''debt-like item'' in the EV-to-equity bridge?', '["Trade payables in the normal course of business","An underfunded pension obligation, an outstanding earn-out from a prior acquisition, and unrecognised tax liabilities from ongoing disputes","Inventory and receivables","Retained earnings"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Debt-like items are obligations that resemble debt in economic substance even if not classified as financial debt on the balance sheet. Common examples: underfunded pensions (future cash obligations), earn-out liabilities from prior acquisitions, unrecognised tax obligations, onerous contracts, contingent liabilities with reasonable probability, and post-employment benefits. These are deducted from EV to determine equity value. Failing to identify debt-like items results in the buyer effectively assuming hidden obligations.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target has €30M of operating lease commitments under IFRS 16 treatment. How does this affect the EV-to-equity bridge?', '["No effect — operating leases are not considered debt","Under IFRS 16, operating leases are recognised as debt-like items and typically added to EV in the debt calculation; for EBITDA multiples, the decision depends on whether EBITDA is pre- or post-IFRS 16","Operating leases are subtracted from cash","Operating leases are ignored for private company transactions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Under IFRS 16 (effective 2019), operating leases are brought onto the balance sheet as right-of-use assets and lease liabilities. This means lease liabilities (previously off-balance-sheet) are now debt-like items in the EV-to-equity bridge. The complication is that lease payments, which previously appeared in EBITDA, are now replaced by depreciation and interest — so the multiplier matters. Sophisticated PE buyers adjust consistently to avoid double-counting or missing the impact.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A minority (non-controlling) interest of 10% exists in one of the target''s subsidiaries. How does this affect the enterprise value calculation?', '["Nothing — it''s already included in equity value","The fair value of the minority interest (the 10% stake held by external parties) is typically added to EV because EV represents the total operations; the PE buyer pays for 100% of the subsidiary''s operations even though they own only 90%","The minority interest is subtracted from cash","The minority interest converts to debt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When calculating EV from equity value, the minority (non-controlling) interest is added because it represents a claim on consolidated operations not owned by the parent. EV represents the total value of operations — you''re pricing the business as if acquiring 100%. Even if the PE buyer only acquires the controlling stake, the business operates at 100%. Formula: EV = Equity Value + Net Debt + Minority Interest (fair value) + Debt-Like Items – Non-Operating Assets.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target has a 30% investment in an associate company valued at €25M on the balance sheet. How is this treated in the EV calculation?', '["Added to EV","Typically subtracted from EV (treated as a non-operating asset) because the associate''s operations are not consolidated and the investment is a separate asset the buyer acquires — often excluded from operating EBITDA as well to maintain consistency","Multiplied by the EV multiple","Ignored entirely"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Investments in associates (typically 20-50% stakes) are equity investments accounted for under the equity method. The associate''s operations are not consolidated — the investment appears as a single line on the balance sheet, and income appears as ''share of associate''s profit'' in the P&L. For EV analysis: subtract the associate investment from the main EV calculation (it''s a non-operating asset), and exclude associate income from operating EBITDA. Otherwise you''re double-counting.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'The EV/EBITDA multiple is a common valuation tool. Why is it preferred over the Price/Earnings (P/E) ratio for PE analysis?', '["EV/EBITDA is always higher than P/E","EV/EBITDA is capital-structure-neutral, while P/E is affected by debt level — a highly leveraged company will have lower P/E than an unleveraged one even if operations are identical","P/E is not used in PE","EV/EBITDA is only useful for tech companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'P/E (Price/Earnings) measures equity price per unit of after-tax earnings. It''s affected by capital structure because higher leverage means higher interest expense, reducing net income and thus raising P/E for a given equity price. EV/EBITDA removes this distortion by using EV (includes debt) in the numerator and EBITDA (before interest) in the denominator. This makes it capital-structure-neutral and better suited for PE analysis where the buyer will change the capital structure.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target''s EV is €500M. Net debt is €150M, and minority interest is €25M. What is the equity value?', '["€375M — EV minus net debt","€325M — EV minus net debt minus minority interest","€675M — EV plus net debt and minority interest","€525M — EV plus minority interest"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Equity Value = EV – Net Debt – Minority Interest (+ Non-Operating Assets if applicable) = €500M – €150M – €25M = €325M. The minority interest is subtracted because it represents the portion of operations owned by external parties in subsidiaries — not accruing to the parent''s equity holders. This €325M is what the parent''s equity holders collectively receive if the business is sold at a €500M EV.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target is valued at €800M EV. The company has €200M of debt, €80M of cash, and an underfunded pension of €40M. What equity value does the PE firm actually pay?', '["€640M — EV less all items","€800M — the full EV","€680M — EV less debt plus cash less pension deficit = €800M – €200M + €80M – €40M","Cannot be determined"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Equity Value = EV – Debt + Cash – Debt-Like Items = €800M – €200M + €80M – €40M = €640M. Wait, the correct answer is actually: EV – Net Debt – Debt-Like Items = €800M – (€200M – €80M) – €40M = €800M – €120M – €40M = €640M. Both formulations produce the same answer. The equity value of €640M is what equity holders receive; the buyer pays this plus assumes the €200M debt (net of €80M cash refund and covering €40M pension), totalling the €800M EV economically.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE-backed company has EV of €350M at acquisition. Four years later, EBITDA has grown 40% and the company has repaid €80M of debt. Enterprise value at exit is €520M (representing the same EV/EBITDA multiple). How does equity value change if entry debt was €200M?', '["Equity value is unchanged","Entry equity was €150M (€350M – €200M); exit equity is €400M (€520M – €120M remaining debt); equity grew by €250M (2.7x MOIC) driven by EBITDA growth and debt paydown","Equity value decreases","Cannot be determined"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Entry: EV €350M – Debt €200M = Equity €150M. Exit: EV €520M – Remaining Debt €120M (€200M – €80M paydown) = Equity €400M. MOIC = €400M / €150M = 2.67x. Even though EV only grew 49% (€350M to €520M), equity grew 167% — illustrating how leverage amplifies returns. EBITDA growth drives EV up, debt paydown reduces debt, and both flow through as equity value.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE buyer''s ''locked box'' deal structure fixes equity value at €300M based on the June balance sheet, with closing in October. What risk does this structure create for the buyer?', '["No risk — everything is fixed","The buyer bears the risk of cash leakage between the locked box date and closing — deteriorating working capital, unusual dividends, or asset sales that reduce the value they receive relative to what was locked in","The seller pays less","The deal cannot close"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A locked box structure fixes economic transfer from a historical balance sheet date (not closing). The purchase price is fixed; no post-closing adjustment. Between locked box date and closing, the seller operates the business ''for the buyer''s benefit.'' Risk for the buyer: value leaks from the locked box (poor working capital management, unusual transactions). The SPA requires the seller to warrant no ''leakage'' — unusual dividends, above-market payments to affiliates, asset sales not in the ordinary course.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A ''completion accounts'' deal structure involves calculating working capital, net debt, and cash at closing, then adjusting the purchase price accordingly. Compared to locked box, what is the key difference?', '["Completion accounts involve no price adjustment","Completion accounts adjust the price based on actual closing date figures rather than a fixed historical amount — reducing the buyer''s risk of value leakage but requiring post-closing reconciliation and potential disputes","Completion accounts are only used for large deals","Completion accounts cost less than locked box"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Completion accounts (also called ''post-closing adjustments'') true-up the purchase price based on actual closing-date working capital, cash, and net debt. The buyer pays/receives the difference between expected and actual. This structure protects buyers from value leakage but creates: (1) closing-date calculation complexity, (2) post-closing disputes about accounting treatment, (3) 30-90 day true-up window. Locked box is typically simpler; completion accounts are common for larger, more complex deals.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target has €45M of ''deferred consideration'' owed to the sellers of a business it acquired 18 months ago. How is this treated in the EV bridge?', '["Excluded entirely","Treated as a debt-like item and deducted from EV when calculating equity value — this is essentially outstanding purchase price that the new buyer is inheriting","Added to cash","Multiplied by the EV multiple"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Deferred consideration (vendor loans, earn-outs, holdbacks from prior acquisitions) represents purchase price for earlier deals that remains unpaid. The new PE buyer is effectively inheriting this obligation — it''s debt-like. Treatment: subtract from EV to determine equity value. Similarly, earn-out liabilities contingent on future performance are typically treated as debt-like using an estimate of probable payout. This prevents the new buyer from double-counting prior acquisition costs.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A company has €25M of ''restricted cash'' on its balance sheet held as collateral for a customer contract. How is this treated in the EV-to-equity bridge?', '["Netted against debt as normal cash","Excluded from the debt netting calculation because it is not freely available to the company — it is pledged for a specific purpose and cannot be used for general corporate needs or debt repayment","Added to EV","Subtracted from EV"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Restricted cash (escrows, collateral deposits, regulatory reserves, customer deposits in some sectors) is not freely available and cannot be used to offset debt. It''s economically different from surplus cash. In the EV bridge, restricted cash is typically excluded from the cash netting calculation — meaning it doesn''t reduce the debt burden. Only ''free'' cash (surplus, unencumbered) qualifies for debt netting. The distinction preserves accurate economic accounting.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target has €100M of ''preference shares'' outstanding that pay a guaranteed 7% dividend and are redeemable in 5 years. How should these be treated in EV analysis?', '["Treated as pure equity","Treated as debt-like (or ''quasi-equity'') in the EV bridge — preference shares with dividend obligations and redemption features behave economically more like debt than common equity, and should be deducted from EV alongside financial debt","Ignored entirely","Added to cash"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Preference shares with fixed dividends and redemption features are economically similar to debt, even though legally they are equity. Under modern analysis, they are typically treated as debt-like items in the EV bridge: subtracted from EV to determine common equity value. Classification depends on the specific terms: perpetual preference shares without redemption may be closer to equity; redeemable preference shares with cumulative dividends are closer to debt. The treatment affects both pricing and return calculations.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target has €150M of convertible debt outstanding that converts to equity at €10/share. The company''s current share price is €15. How should this be treated?', '["Treated as pure debt","Treated as equity (because conversion is economically advantageous — the debt will likely convert rather than be repaid in cash), effectively reducing the current debt position but adding to the equity share count","Ignored","Added to EV twice"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When convertible debt is ''in the money'' (conversion advantageous to the holder), it will likely convert to equity rather than be repaid. In this case, treat it as equity: include the converted shares in the share count for equity value calculation. When convertible debt is ''out of the money,'' treat it as debt. The distinction matters for both EV bridge accuracy and for understanding post-transaction share count in the PE firm''s capital structure.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target''s EBITDA is €45M and it trades at a 10x EV multiple. What is the implied EV?', '["€450M","€45M × 10 = €450M","€4.5M","€4,500M"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EV = EV/EBITDA multiple × EBITDA = 10 × €45M = €450M. This is the fundamental arithmetic of multiple-based valuation. Sophisticated analysis goes beyond this simple calculation to: validate the EBITDA figure (adjusted vs reported), select appropriate multiples (LTM vs NTM, peer-based vs transaction-based), apply control/size premiums, and reconcile across valuation methodologies (DCF cross-check).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'An LBO model uses LTM adjusted EBITDA of €30M. If the PE firm pays €270M at 9.0x, what is the equity check required assuming €180M of LBO debt is raised?', '["€270M — full EV","€90M — EV minus the debt financing = €270M – €180M","€450M — EV plus debt","€180M — equal to the debt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Equity check = EV – Debt raised = €270M – €180M = €90M. This is the PE fund''s equity investment at closing. The €180M of debt is raised from lenders; the remaining €90M comes from the fund''s equity. Together they fund the €270M EV acquisition (plus transaction fees). The equity check directly determines return potential: every €1M of EBITDA growth times the exit multiple flows through to equity, amplified by the leverage ratio.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE buyer calculates an initial ''LBO-based'' maximum EV. What does this represent?', '["The absolute minimum price the seller will accept","The maximum EV the buyer can pay while still generating an acceptable IRR (typically 20-25%) given specific assumptions about debt, EBITDA growth, and exit multiple","The price a public market investor would pay","The book value of the company"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LBO-based maximum EV works backward from required returns: given a target IRR (say 22%), projected EBITDA growth, expected exit multiple, and debt capacity, what is the maximum entry EV that still delivers the target IRR? This is the PE firm''s ''ability to pay'' ceiling — they shouldn''t bid above this level regardless of market conditions. Comparable public/deal multiples are reference points; LBO math sets the discipline. If market pricing exceeds LBO-derived max, the PE firm must walk away or cut the target return.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target''s balance sheet shows €220M of ''long-term debt'' and €15M of ''current portion of long-term debt.'' How are both treated in the net debt calculation?', '["Only long-term debt is included","Both are treated as debt for net debt calculation — current portion is debt that simply becomes due within 12 months; economically it''s the same obligation, just nearer to repayment","Only the current portion is included","Neither is considered debt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Total financial debt includes all interest-bearing obligations regardless of maturity: short-term debt, current portion of long-term debt, long-term debt, bonds, notes, etc. The ''current portion'' is simply long-term debt that becomes due within 12 months — it''s the same debt, just reclassified by maturity on the balance sheet. All of it is deducted in the EV-to-equity bridge. Only truly non-interest-bearing trade payables are excluded from debt.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE buyer adjusts EV for ''non-operating assets'' such as excess real estate or investment securities. Why?', '["To inflate the EV","Non-operating assets don''t contribute to operating EBITDA, so they shouldn''t be valued using the operating EV multiple; they are valued separately at fair market value and added to the operating EV to arrive at total EV","To hide the acquisition cost","Non-operating assets are always excluded from EV"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Non-operating assets (excess real estate not used in operations, investment securities, non-core subsidiaries) don''t generate the EBITDA being multiplied. Valuing them at the operating multiple would double-count or mis-price. Instead: (1) value operating business using EV/EBITDA on operating EBITDA; (2) value non-operating assets separately at market value (e.g., real estate appraisals, investment marks); (3) sum to total enterprise value. This ''sum-of-parts'' approach prevents valuation errors.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'During diligence, a buyer discovers €20M of ''off-balance-sheet'' operating lease commitments that the seller claims are ''non-debt.'' Under modern PE analysis, how are these treated?', '["Ignored as non-debt","Under IFRS 16 and modern analysis, operating leases are treated as debt-like items in the EV bridge — if not already on the balance sheet, the PE buyer adjusts the deal pricing to reflect this commitment","Tripled for conservatism","Added to working capital"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Post-IFRS 16, operating leases are brought onto the balance sheet as liabilities. For private deals where accounting may lag, the PE buyer adjusts manually: €20M of lease commitments represents a real financial obligation that reduces the equity value. Treatment: add to the debt figure in the EV bridge, or deduct the lease liability from EV to reach equity value. Consistency matters — if lease expense was added back to EBITDA, the corresponding liability must appear in the bridge.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A seller presents a target at ''€450M EV'' based on 10x LTM EBITDA of €45M. The buyer''s QofE reduces adjusted EBITDA to €40M. What is the implied EV at the same multiple?', '["€450M — remains the same","€400M — €40M × 10 = €400M, a €50M reduction due to the lower EBITDA","€500M — multiplied by a different factor","Cannot be calculated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EV = 10 × €40M = €400M, not €450M. This illustrates why EBITDA accuracy matters so much in deal pricing. A €5M QofE adjustment translates to €50M of EV reduction (€5M × 10x). This is why QofE is fundamental to PE deal pricing: seemingly small adjustments compound through the multiple. Negotiations often revolve around whose EBITDA view is accepted. Sophisticated buyers avoid walking away when QofE reveals €5M less EBITDA; they negotiate the price accordingly.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE buyer is structuring a deal where the seller will retain 20% equity (rollover equity). How does this affect the EV calculation?', '["The rollover reduces the EV","The EV calculation is unchanged; the rollover reduces the PE firm''s equity check by 20% (the seller retains €X of the €Y required equity), but the business is still acquired at the same total EV","The rollover eliminates the need for debt","The EV doubles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rollover equity doesn''t change the EV — the business is still being acquired at the same enterprise value. What changes is the funding mix: the required equity check is split between the PE fund and the rollover seller. If €100M equity is needed and the seller rolls 20%, the fund invests €80M and the seller retains €20M of equity in the new business. This aligns incentives (seller still has skin in the game) while reducing the PE firm''s own capital deployment.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A target''s ''cash and cash equivalents'' line is €85M. Closer review reveals €60M is in an overseas subsidiary with €12M in withholding tax if repatriated, and €15M is ''trapped'' in a regulated subsidiary requiring regulatory approval to extract. What is the effective cash position for EV purposes?', '["€85M — the reported cash balance","Approximately €58M or less — accounting for tax friction (€12M withholding on €60M) and regulatory constraints on €15M that may not be freely available","€0 — cash is never freely available","Double the amount for flexibility"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Not all cash is equal. Repatriation tax friction, regulatory restrictions, and operational requirements reduce the economic value of cash. Starting from €85M: subtract €12M of withholding tax on overseas cash (= €73M), assess the €15M regulated subsidiary restrictions (may be inaccessible). Effective free cash for EV purposes is approximately €58M or less. This matters because the buyer''s equity check is increased by the cash that cannot actually be accessed for debt paydown.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE firm''s investment memo presents an ''EV at exit'' of €600M assuming 10x exit multiple on €60M EBITDA. Upon review, what additional assumption matters for equity returns?', '["Only the EBITDA figure","The remaining debt at exit also matters — exit equity = €600M EV – remaining debt; the pace of debt paydown during the hold materially affects final equity value and therefore MOIC/IRR","The exit multiple alone","The exit year is irrelevant"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Exit EV of €600M is only half the picture. Exit Equity = EV – Remaining Debt. If €300M of debt was repaid during the hold (from initial €350M), remaining debt = €50M, exit equity = €550M. If only €100M was repaid, remaining debt = €250M, exit equity = €350M. This €200M swing in equity value reflects the importance of debt paydown in LBO returns. Model assumptions about cash flow, capex, working capital, and discretionary uses of cash all feed into the debt paydown projection.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'An investment banker''s pitch shows a target''s ''equity value'' of €250M with €100M of debt. A junior analyst asks why the EV (which is what PE firms typically price on) isn''t stated. What is the EV?', '["€250M","€350M — equity value plus debt (€250M + €100M)","€150M — equity value minus debt","Cannot be calculated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Starting from equity value: EV = Equity Value + Debt – Cash + Debt-Like Items – Non-Operating Assets. If net debt is €100M and no debt-like items: EV = €250M + €100M = €350M. PE firms typically present EV first (since they''re agnostic to capital structure), while equity-market-focused materials may start with equity value. Converting between the two simply requires the net debt figure.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE firm analyses ''EV per unit of capacity'' for an infrastructure target. Why might this metric supplement EV/EBITDA analysis?', '["It doesn''t — EV/EBITDA is always sufficient","For infrastructure, real estate, or capacity-constrained businesses, EV per unit of physical capacity (€/kilowatt for power, €/unit for manufacturing, €/subscriber for telecoms) provides an alternative view grounded in the underlying asset base","It''s required by regulators","It''s used only for tax planning"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EV per unit metrics provide asset-intensity-based valuation: €/KW for power plants, €/subscriber for telcos, €/bed for hospitals, €/square metre for retail. These metrics work alongside EV/EBITDA by grounding valuation in physical assets. For capacity-constrained businesses with relatively consistent unit economics, peer deals on a per-unit basis provide an alternative sanity check. This is particularly useful for infrastructure, real estate, and certain regulated industries.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE buyer notes that two comparable public companies trade at EV/Revenue multiples of 2.8x and 3.2x. The target generates €200M of revenue. How could this be applied?', '["Only for startups","EV = average multiple × Revenue = 3.0 × €200M = €600M — provides a revenue-based valuation reference, particularly useful for growth companies, early-stage businesses, or when EBITDA is distorted or negative","This is never a valid approach","Only for loss-making businesses"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EV/Revenue is particularly useful when: EBITDA is distorted (unprofitable growth investment), approaching zero, or heavily adjusted; companies have very different operating models obscuring EBITDA comparability; early-stage businesses where revenue growth is the primary metric. Application: EV = 3.0 × €200M = €600M. Limitations: ignores profitability, assumes revenue quality is similar across peers, and can mislead for heavily differentiated business models with divergent margin profiles.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE firm is structuring a deal where part of the consideration is ''vendor financing'' — the seller extends a €30M loan to the buyer to fund part of the acquisition. How does this affect the EV calculation?', '["Vendor financing reduces the EV","EV remains unchanged; vendor financing is a funding source (like bank debt) that reduces the PE firm''s required equity check but doesn''t affect the transaction value","Vendor financing doubles the EV","Vendor financing is not allowed"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Vendor financing is an alternative funding source that doesn''t change the EV — it changes how the acquisition is funded. The PE firm still acquires the business at the negotiated EV (say €300M); the funding mix shifts from equity+bank debt to equity+bank debt+vendor loan. Economically, vendor loans are debt-like (typically with interest, repayment terms, possibly collateral). They''re useful when bank financing is constrained or when aligning seller interests through deferred consideration.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE buyer is assessing a target''s working capital normalisation. The company shows €25M of working capital at closing. Over the past 3 years, average working capital was €35M. Why does this difference matter?', '["It doesn''t matter","The €10M deficit (€35M expected vs €25M at closing) means the seller has extracted €10M of working capital before closing — either through aggressive AR collection, payable stretching, or inventory reduction; the purchase price should be reduced by €10M to compensate the buyer","The seller should receive a bonus","Working capital doesn''t affect deal pricing"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Working capital normalisation protects against seller manipulation of working capital near closing. If historical average is €35M but closing is €25M, the seller has extracted €10M of ''business value'' that should normally be part of the deal. The SPA''s working capital adjustment mechanism reduces the purchase price by €10M to compensate. Without this adjustment, the buyer inherits a business with €10M less working capital than normal — either requiring €10M additional investment or experiencing operational difficulties.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE firm''s LBO model shows entry EV of €400M, exit EV of €560M (5 years later), and remaining debt at exit of €150M (down from €240M at entry). What is the equity return?', '["€400M — same as entry EV","Entry equity = €400M – €240M = €160M; exit equity = €560M – €150M = €410M; equity grew 2.56x, reflecting both EV growth and debt paydown","€560M — same as exit EV","€0 — no return"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The equity return decomposition: Entry Equity = €160M. Exit Equity = €410M. Growth = €250M = 2.56x MOIC. Drivers: EV growth (€160M) + Debt paydown (€90M) = €250M total equity growth. Both drivers contribute: 64% from EV appreciation, 36% from debt paydown. Understanding this decomposition is central to PE analysis — it separates operational value creation (EV/EBITDA growth) from financial engineering (debt paydown) in generating returns.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'A PE analyst is comparing two targets with identical EBITDA of €50M. Target A has €100M of pension deficit; Target B has none. How should this affect the pricing comparison?', '["Both targets should be priced identically at the same multiple","Target A''s equity value should be €100M lower than Target B''s at the same operating EV — the pension deficit is a debt-like item the buyer must assume; if both are priced at 10x EBITDA (€500M EV), Target A''s equity = €400M while Target B''s = €500M","Target A should have a higher multiple","Target A is more attractive because it has pension obligations"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Both targets have identical operating performance (€50M EBITDA), justifying the same EV multiple. But Target A has a €100M pension deficit — a debt-like obligation the buyer assumes. At 10x EBITDA: Target A EV = €500M; equity = €500M – €100M pension = €400M. Target B EV = €500M; equity = €500M (no deficit). The buyer should pay €100M less for Target A''s equity than Target B''s, reflecting the economic reality that pensions are debt-like claims.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-enterprise-value', 'Why is understanding the distinction between ''Enterprise Value'' and ''Equity Value'' so central to PE practice?', '["Only lenders care about this distinction","EV is how PE firms think about business value (capital-structure-neutral), while equity value is what PE firms actually pay in cash plus assume in debt — the bridge between them contains all the pricing negotiations around debt, working capital, pensions, and other debt-like items","They are identical in PE practice","EV is only used for public companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The EV-to-equity bridge is where PE deal pricing actually happens. EV represents the ''clean'' business value (the seller''s and buyer''s views converge here through multiples analysis). The bridge — containing debt, cash, working capital, pensions, earn-outs, and other items — is where negotiation occurs. Each €1 in the bridge flows dollar-for-dollar to equity value (not multiplied). This is why the bridge is scrutinised carefully during QofE and why the seller typically wants the bridge to favor them at every line.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A PE associate is reviewing a target''s three financial statements. Which statement is most critical for LBO analysis, and why?', '["The income statement, because it shows revenue growth and net income trends","The balance sheet, because it shows the company''s assets that will collateralise the acquisition debt","The cash flow statement, because PE returns depend on cash generation to service debt","All three are equally important and cannot be ranked"]'::jsonb, 2, 'PE returns are driven by cash, not accounting profits. The cash flow statement reveals whether EBITDA actually converts to free cash flow — which is what services the acquisition debt. A business with strong reported earnings but weak cash generation is a poor LBO candidate regardless of what the income statement shows.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'During diligence, an associate notices that a target''s revenue grew 18% year-over-year while accounts receivable grew 42% over the same period. What is the most likely concern this raises?', '["The company is growing too quickly and risks operational strain","Revenue may be recognised prematurely or customers are paying more slowly","Working capital is being optimised, which is a positive sign","Nothing — growing receivables is a normal consequence of revenue growth"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Receivables growing more than twice as fast as revenue signals either aggressive revenue recognition (booking revenue before collection is probable) or a deterioration in payment terms (customers paying later). Either way, cash conversion is weakening. This is a red flag that warrants investigation during quality of earnings analysis.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target company reports capex of 2.5% of revenue, while industry peers average 5.5%. What should a PE buyer conclude?', '["The target is more capital-efficient than peers, which is attractive","The target may be underinvesting, creating a hidden liability for the buyer","The target operates an asset-light model and should be valued at a premium","Capex ratios are not meaningful for cross-company comparison"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Consistently below-industry capex often signals deferred maintenance or underinvestment — creating a hidden future obligation the buyer will need to fund post-acquisition. The distinction between maintenance capex (sustaining current operations) and growth capex (expanding capacity) matters: if maintenance capex has been starved, the business may require significant catch-up investment.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A PE firm is analysing normalisation adjustments for a target. Which of the following would most legitimately be added back to arrive at adjusted EBITDA?', '["Annual IT infrastructure upgrade costs that appear in every fiscal year","A one-time legal settlement from a discontinued product line that will not recur","The salary of a key account manager the company cannot operate without","Regulatory compliance costs that have been present for the last five years"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The legitimate test for a normalisation add-back is whether the cost would recur in a normal operating year. A settled lawsuit from a discontinued product line meets that test. Recurring IT upgrades, essential operating salaries, and five-year-recurring compliance costs all fail the test — they are simply part of running the business.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A PE firm conducting due diligence is given three sets of financial information: management accounts (monthly), board-reported figures (quarterly), and audited financial statements (annual). Which should the PE buyer rely on most heavily?', '["Management accounts because they are most recent","Audited financial statements because they have been externally verified, supplemented by management accounts for recent periods after audit","Board-reported figures because they are reviewed by directors","All three are equally reliable"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Audited financials are the anchor — externally verified by independent auditors under accepted accounting standards. Management accounts are useful for recent months but may contain estimates, errors, or management bias. PE diligence typically reconciles management accounts back to audited figures to identify variances that could signal aggressive accounting or forecast manipulation.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'On a typical P&L, which line item represents revenue minus direct costs of producing or delivering goods/services?', '["Net income","Gross profit","EBITDA","Operating income"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gross profit = Revenue – Cost of Goods Sold (COGS). It measures the profitability of core product/service delivery before operating expenses (sales, marketing, G&A). Gross margin (Gross profit / Revenue) is a key indicator of pricing power, scale economics, and competitive position. Software companies typically show 70-85% gross margins; industrial companies 25-45%.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s P&L shows Operating Income (EBIT) of €18M and EBITDA of €28M. What accounts for the €10M difference?', '["Tax expense of €10M","Depreciation and amortisation of €10M","Interest expense of €10M","Dividends of €10M"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EBITDA = EBIT + D&A. The €10M gap represents the company''s depreciation (fixed asset wear-down) and amortisation (intangible asset write-off) charges. Both are non-cash accounting entries that reduce reported profit but don''t affect cash flow. PE firms focus on EBITDA because it''s closer to cash-generating capacity, though D&A eventually shows up as capex in the cash flow statement.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'Why do PE professionals typically focus on EBITDA rather than net income when evaluating target companies?', '["EBITDA is always higher than net income, making returns look better","EBITDA isolates operating performance by removing financing structure (interest), tax jurisdiction, and non-cash items (D&A) — providing a cleaner comparison across companies","Net income is manipulated by accounting rules while EBITDA is not","EBITDA is the only measure accepted by regulators"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EBITDA normalises for capital structure (removing interest expense), tax regime (removing tax), and non-cash accounting (removing D&A) — isolating the company''s ability to generate operating cash flow. This makes it useful for comparing companies with different debt levels, tax jurisdictions, or asset bases. However, EBITDA is not a perfect proxy for cash: it ignores capex requirements, working capital changes, and actual cash taxes.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'An income statement reports strong net income but the cash flow statement reveals negative operating cash flow. What might explain this divergence?', '["The company is clearly committing fraud","Accrual accounting recognises revenue and expenses based on when transactions occur, not when cash moves; the gap may reflect growing receivables, inventory build, or revenue recognised before cash collection","Net income and cash flow are always identical, so one must be wrong","The cash flow statement is less reliable than the income statement"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Accrual accounting creates gaps between reported profit and cash. Common causes: receivables growing (sales made, cash not yet collected), inventory building (cash spent on goods not yet sold), paying down deferred revenue (cash collected in prior periods is recognised as revenue now). Not all gaps indicate problems — growing businesses often consume cash — but systematic, unexplained divergence warrants investigation.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'The balance sheet follows a fundamental accounting equation. Which of the following represents this identity?', '["Revenue = Expenses + Profit","Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders'' Equity","Cash Flow = Net Income + Depreciation","Equity = Revenue – Costs"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The balance sheet equation Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders'' Equity is the foundation of double-entry accounting. It expresses that everything the company owns (assets) was funded either by creditors (liabilities) or shareholders (equity). This equation must always hold; any balance sheet that doesn''t balance signals an accounting error. Changes in assets must match changes in liabilities plus equity.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s balance sheet distinguishes between ''current'' and ''non-current'' assets. What defines this classification?', '["Current assets are tangible; non-current assets are intangible","Current assets are expected to be converted to cash or consumed within 12 months; non-current assets are held longer","Current assets are valuable; non-current assets are not","There is no accepted distinction"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Current assets (cash, receivables, inventory, prepaid expenses) are expected to be converted to cash or consumed within one year. Non-current assets (PP&E, goodwill, intangibles, long-term investments) have longer useful lives. The distinction matters for liquidity analysis: current assets fund current liabilities, and the difference (working capital) indicates short-term financial health.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s accounts receivable aging schedule shows 35% of receivables are over 90 days past due. What does this suggest about the business?', '["This is a healthy pattern showing robust customer relationships","Significant collection risk — receivables this old are increasingly likely to become bad debts, suggesting weak credit control, deteriorating customer quality, or disputes","The business is growing too fast","This is typical for all industries"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A healthy AR aging typically shows most receivables in the 0-30 and 30-60 day buckets. 35% over 90 days is highly unusual and suggests: poor credit control processes, customer payment disputes, financial distress among customers, or weak enforcement of terms. This directly affects cash conversion, valuation of receivables (potential write-downs), and the quality of reported revenue.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target uses LIFO (Last In First Out) inventory valuation while peers use FIFO (First In First Out). In a period of rising prices, what effect does this have on reported results?', '["No difference — both methods produce identical results","LIFO typically reports higher COGS, lower gross profit, and lower inventory values on the balance sheet during inflation","LIFO always produces higher profits","Only FIFO is allowed under modern accounting standards"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Under LIFO, the most recently purchased (typically most expensive) inventory is expensed first, producing higher COGS and lower reported profits during inflation. FIFO expenses older (cheaper) inventory first, producing higher profits. LIFO is permitted under US GAAP but prohibited under IFRS. When comparing companies using different methods, the analyst must adjust for the difference to make results comparable.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s balance sheet shows €85M of goodwill and €25M of other intangible assets. What do these represent, and why do they matter for PE analysis?', '["They are imaginary assets with no economic meaning","Goodwill represents the premium paid above net identifiable assets in past acquisitions; intangibles represent separately identifiable non-physical assets (brands, customer lists, technology) — both reflect the company''s acquisition history","They are tax deductions available to the buyer","They must be liquidated before a PE acquisition"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Goodwill arises from past acquisitions: the excess of purchase price over the fair value of identifiable net assets. Intangibles include specifically identifiable assets (trademarks, patents, customer relationships, developed technology). Under IFRS, goodwill is tested for impairment annually rather than amortised. In PE analysis, goodwill reveals acquisition history; large impairments signal past overpayment; substantial intangibles may require amortisation expense consideration.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A SaaS company''s balance sheet shows €30M of ''deferred revenue'' as a liability. What does this represent?', '["Revenue that was never collected and is considered uncollectable","Cash collected from customers for services to be delivered in future periods — representing a liability to deliver those services, not yet recognised as revenue","Revenue hidden by management for tax purposes","A form of customer deposit for returned products"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Deferred revenue (also called ''unearned revenue'') represents customer prepayments for services not yet delivered. It is a liability because the company owes the customer future delivery. For SaaS companies, annual subscriptions create deferred revenue that''s recognised monthly as service is delivered. High deferred revenue is typically positive: it indicates strong cash collection, locked-in future revenue, and customer commitment.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s balance sheet shows trade payables of €45M against COGS of €270M annually. What is the implied Days Payable Outstanding (DPO)?', '["Approximately 61 days","Approximately 17 days","Approximately 6 days","Cannot be calculated from the information given"]'::jsonb, 0, 'DPO = (Accounts Payable / COGS) × 365 = (€45M / €270M) × 365 ≈ 61 days. This means the company pays suppliers, on average, 61 days after receiving goods. DPO is a working capital lever: higher DPO means more favourable payment terms and better cash retention. Benchmarking DPO against industry peers reveals whether the company has negotiated strong supplier terms or is paying earlier than necessary.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s ''retained earnings'' has grown from €85M to €125M over three years. What does this growth represent?', '["The company has received €40M in new capital contributions","The cumulative after-tax profits generated over those three years that have not been distributed to shareholders","The value of the company''s assets has increased by €40M","The company has borrowed €40M from lenders"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Retained earnings represents cumulative after-tax profits not distributed as dividends. The €40M growth equals: Net Income (over 3 years) minus dividends paid. This line shows how much profit the company has reinvested into the business. PE buyers often find retained earnings useful for understanding historical dividend policy and the potential for cash extraction during ownership.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A company''s balance sheet shows ''Share Capital'' of €1M and ''Share Premium'' of €24M. What distinguishes these two items?', '["They are identical line items","Share Capital represents the nominal/par value of issued shares; Share Premium represents amounts paid above par value by investors during share issuance","Share Premium is a liability, Share Capital is equity","Share Premium must be distributed as dividends"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Share Capital records the nominal value (par) of issued shares (often €0.01 or €1 per share). Share Premium records the amount investors paid above par. If shares with €1 par were issued at €25 each, €1 is share capital and €24 is share premium. Both are forms of equity but are tracked separately. Share premium can be used for bonus issues or, in some jurisdictions, dividends subject to specific rules.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s notes to the financial statements disclose a ''contingent liability'' of €15M related to ongoing litigation. What does this mean for a PE buyer?', '["The target must pay €15M immediately at closing","A potential future obligation whose amount and timing are uncertain, which must be factored into risk assessment, deal structuring (indemnities, escrows), and potentially pricing","The amount is guaranteed to become payable","Contingent liabilities can be ignored in PE analysis"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Contingent liabilities are potential obligations that may arise depending on future events (e.g., litigation outcome, warranty claims, regulatory penalties). They are disclosed rather than recorded because the amount or probability is uncertain. PE buyers assess the likelihood of these becoming real liabilities, size them in downside scenarios, and may require indemnities from the seller, purchase price adjustments, or escrow arrangements to cover the risk.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'The cash flow statement is divided into three sections. What do they represent?', '["Historical, current, and projected cash flows","Operating activities (cash from core operations), investing activities (cash from asset purchases/sales), and financing activities (cash from debt/equity)","Cash receipts, cash payments, and cash reserves","Monthly, quarterly, and annual cash flows"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The cash flow statement separates cash flows by source: (1) Operating — cash generated by core business operations; (2) Investing — cash from buying/selling long-term assets (capex, acquisitions, asset disposals); (3) Financing — cash from capital providers (debt issuance/repayment, equity issuance/buybacks, dividends). The sum of these three sections plus opening cash equals closing cash.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'Using the indirect method, the cash flow statement typically starts with which line item?', '["Cash received from customers","Net income, adjusted for non-cash items (depreciation, amortisation, stock compensation) and changes in working capital","Revenue","Total cash balance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The indirect method (most common) starts with Net Income and reconciles to operating cash flow through adjustments: adding back non-cash charges (D&A, SBC, impairments), subtracting non-cash income (gains on sale), and adjusting for changes in working capital (receivables, payables, inventory, accrued expenses). The direct method (less common) lists actual cash receipts and payments by category.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A PE analyst computes ''Free Cash Flow'' for a target. Which formula typically applies?', '["Revenue minus Expenses","Operating Cash Flow minus Capex — representing cash available after maintaining and growing operational capacity","Net Income plus Depreciation","EBITDA minus Taxes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Free Cash Flow (FCF) = Operating Cash Flow – Capex. It measures cash available to capital providers (debt and equity) after the business has reinvested in its operations. For PE analysis, FCF is critical because it''s what services debt and generates returns. Some analysts further distinguish ''Levered FCF'' (after debt service) from ''Unlevered FCF'' (before debt service, used for EV-based valuation).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'Capital expenditure (capex) appears in which section of the cash flow statement?', '["Operating activities as a non-cash charge","Investing activities, typically as a cash outflow","Financing activities as a form of debt repayment","As a separate standalone line item"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Capex represents investment in long-term productive assets (buildings, machinery, technology). It flows through investing activities as a cash outflow. Note that depreciation is already handled in the operating section (added back as non-cash) — capex and depreciation are related: over time, capex should approximately match depreciation for a steady-state business, though not necessarily in any single year.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A company issues €200M of new long-term debt and repays €50M of short-term borrowings in the same year. How are these reported on the cash flow statement?', '["Both appear in operating activities","Both appear in financing activities: €200M as proceeds from debt issuance (inflow), €50M as debt repayment (outflow)","Both appear in investing activities","They are netted and show €150M as operating cash flow"]'::jsonb, 1, 'All debt-related cash movements flow through financing activities: borrowing proceeds (inflow), principal repayments (outflow), bond issuance, debt repurchases. Interest payments, however, typically appear in operating activities (reflecting ongoing debt service). This section also includes equity transactions: share issuance, buybacks, and dividends. PE buyers watch financing activities closely to understand capital structure changes.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A company reports net income of €50M but operating cash flow of €72M. The primary reason for the €22M gap is typically:', '["Accounting fraud","Non-cash charges (depreciation, amortisation, stock-based compensation) being added back plus favourable working capital changes","Interest expense","Tax timing differences"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The most common reason operating cash flow exceeds net income is non-cash charges being added back (particularly depreciation, amortisation, and stock-based compensation) plus favourable working capital changes. If a company has €20M of annual D&A and €2M of working capital benefit, net income of €50M reconciles to operating cash flow of €72M. This is a healthy sign — the company is earning real profits that translate to real cash.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A technology company reports stock-based compensation (SBC) expense of €8M annually. How does this affect the income statement and cash flow statement?', '["It increases net income because it''s a non-cash benefit","It reduces net income as an operating expense on the income statement but is added back as a non-cash charge in operating cash flow","It appears only on the balance sheet","It''s hidden from all financial statements"]'::jsonb, 1, 'SBC is a real compensation expense that reduces net income on the income statement. Because it''s paid in equity (not cash), it''s added back to arrive at operating cash flow. This creates a divergence: companies with heavy SBC (particularly tech) often show strong operating cash flow but weaker net income. Debate continues about whether SBC should be ''excluded'' when evaluating cash generation — PE analysts typically treat it as a real economic cost even if non-cash.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'Under IFRS 15 / ASC 606, revenue is recognised based on the transfer of control. A software company sells a 3-year subscription for €300,000 paid upfront. How is revenue typically recognised?', '["€300,000 recognised immediately upon receipt","€100,000 recognised per year over the 3-year service period, with remaining amounts held as deferred revenue","€300,000 recognised over 1 year","Revenue is recognised only when cash is received"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Revenue recognition follows performance obligations being satisfied. For a 3-year subscription, the performance obligation (providing the service) is satisfied ratably over the term. Revenue is typically recognised €100K per year; the remaining €200K (year 1) and €100K (year 2) are deferred revenue on the balance sheet. This matches revenue with service delivery rather than cash timing and is standard practice under IFRS 15.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A PE firm reviewing a distributor notices that the company recorded significant sales in the final two weeks of its fiscal year, with many of those shipments returned in the first month of the next fiscal year. What is this pattern called?', '["Inventory management","Channel stuffing — artificially accelerating sales to customers who may return the product, distorting period financials","Capacity utilisation","Seasonal adjustment"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Channel stuffing involves pushing excessive inventory to distributors or customers near period-end to inflate reported revenue, often through extended payment terms or return privileges. Returns in the following period reveal that reported revenue was not genuine economic activity. Patterns to watch: elevated AR at period-end, high returns post-period, extended payment terms only for period-end sales, concentration of revenue in the final weeks of a quarter.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A construction company uses ''percentage-of-completion'' revenue recognition for long-term contracts. What does this method do?', '["Revenue is recognised only at project completion","Revenue is recognised progressively as the project is completed, based on costs incurred or output delivered relative to total expected","Revenue is recognised when cash is received from the customer","No revenue is recognised until the final invoice"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percentage-of-completion recognises revenue progressively as work is performed on long-term contracts (construction, engineering, defence). If a €100M project is 40% complete by cost-to-cost measurement, €40M of revenue and associated costs are recognised. This method requires estimates about total costs and completion — creating room for manipulation through aggressive estimates of progress or understated remaining costs.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A manufacturer invoices a customer for products stored in the manufacturer''s warehouse ready for delivery. Under accounting rules, this is called:', '["Standard revenue recognition","A ''bill-and-hold'' arrangement, which has strict requirements (customer request, substantial reason for arrangement, products ready and identifiable) to legitimately recognise revenue before delivery","Inventory revaluation","Trade financing"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Bill-and-hold allows revenue recognition when products are not yet delivered but have been billed. Under IFRS 15 / ASC 606, strict criteria must be met: the arrangement must be for the customer''s benefit (not the seller''s earnings management), the products must be separately identifiable as the customer''s, and the goods must be ready for physical transfer. Abusive bill-and-hold has been a source of accounting fraud (e.g., the 1990s Sunbeam scandal).'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'An auditor issues a ''qualified opinion'' on a target''s financial statements. What does this mean?', '["The auditor fully agrees with the statements (clean opinion)","The auditor has identified specific issues where the statements don''t comply with accounting standards, but the overall statements are otherwise fairly presented — requiring investigation of the flagged matters","The statements are completely unreliable","The auditor has not completed the audit"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Audit opinions come in four types: unqualified (clean — no issues identified), qualified (specific concerns but overall statements fairly presented ''except for'' those items), adverse (statements are materially misstated or misleading), and disclaimer (auditor cannot form an opinion). A qualified opinion is a yellow flag that PE buyers must investigate — it may reveal accounting judgement disputes, estimation uncertainties, or limitations on audit scope.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target company''s financial statements include segment reporting that breaks down revenue and EBITDA by business line. Why is this useful for PE analysis?', '["Segment data is meaningless for PE analysis","It reveals the performance, growth, and profitability of each business line separately — supporting sum-of-the-parts valuation, identifying winners/losers within the portfolio, and highlighting divestiture candidates","It is only used for tax purposes","It is only required for public companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Segment reporting (required under IFRS 8 / ASC 280) breaks down financial results by business unit. For PE analysis, this reveals: which business lines are growing vs. declining, relative margin profiles, concentration risk, candidates for divestiture or investment focus. It also enables sum-of-the-parts valuation where different segments might command different multiples. Weak businesses hidden inside a profitable parent often become visible only through segment analysis.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s notes disclose ''related party transactions'' including rent paid to the founder for office space and consulting fees paid to the founder''s spouse. Why do PE buyers scrutinise these?', '["They are always illegal","Related party transactions may be at non-market rates, inflating or deflating reported EBITDA; they must be normalised to market terms to understand true profitability, and the PE buyer must plan for how they will be handled post-acquisition","They have no effect on the business","They are automatically removed in audits"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Related party transactions (between the company and its owners, executives, or their families) may be at above-market rates (inflating the seller''s personal extraction) or below-market (artificially boosting EBITDA). Common examples: rent paid to owner-controlled entities, consulting fees to family members, loans to/from the owner. PE diligence normalises these to market rates — adjusting EBITDA accordingly — and plans for termination or restructuring post-acquisition.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target presents ''Adjusted EBITDA'' of €45M alongside reported EBITDA of €32M (under GAAP). This is an example of:', '["An accounting error","A non-GAAP measure — management-defined adjusted metric that modifies the standard figure for items management believes obscure underlying performance; PE buyers scrutinise every adjustment","A regulatory requirement","A tax calculation"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Non-GAAP measures (Adjusted EBITDA, Pro-Forma Revenue, Normalised Profit, Cash EBITDA) are company-defined metrics that modify standard accounting figures. Management claims they better reflect ''underlying'' performance by removing one-time items, stock compensation, restructuring costs, etc. PE buyers must scrutinise each adjustment: some are legitimate, others represent aggressive reframing of recurring costs as non-recurring. The gap between GAAP and adjusted numbers often signals areas requiring investigation.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A German company with significant UK operations reports its consolidated financials in EUR. A PE buyer analysing year-over-year revenue growth notices that UK revenue grew 12% in GBP but only 3% in EUR. What explains the difference?', '["The company is double-counting revenue","Currency translation effects — GBP weakened against EUR during the period, so UK revenue measured in EUR grew less than in GBP; ''constant currency'' reporting would show the underlying growth","An accounting error","Tax adjustments"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Multinational companies translate foreign subsidiary results into the reporting currency at prevailing exchange rates. If GBP weakened against EUR, UK revenue translates to fewer EUR despite unchanged local-currency performance. This creates translation effects that can obscure underlying business performance. Sophisticated analysts use ''constant currency'' reporting (translating at prior-period rates) to isolate operational growth from currency movements.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s prior-year financial statements are being ''restated'' due to identified errors. What does this signal to a PE buyer?', '["Routine accounting adjustment with no significance","A significant red flag: material errors in previously reported figures indicate weaknesses in financial controls and reporting discipline; PE buyers investigate the nature, magnitude, and root cause of errors","The business has improved","The company is required to apologise"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Restatements correct material errors in previously issued financial statements. They are serious signals of weak internal controls, accounting judgement errors, or potential fraud. PE buyers investigate: what was wrong, how large the errors were, what caused them, whether processes have been corrected, and whether other errors may exist. Restatements often precede management changes, SEC actions, or shareholder litigation.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target company''s balance sheet shows a significant increase in ''inventory'' over the past year without corresponding revenue growth. What concern might this raise?', '["The company is well-prepared for future demand","Inventory build-up without revenue growth may signal weak sales, slow-moving or obsolete stock, aggressive production to meet cost absorption, or accounting errors","The company is being conservatively managed","This is always a positive indicator"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Inventory growing faster than revenue is a common warning sign. Possible causes: declining sales without production adjustment (cost absorption), obsolescence (stale goods not yet written down), aggressive production to inflate reported profit through cost absorption, or overstated inventory valuation. PE diligence investigates through inventory aging analysis, obsolescence reserves review, and physical counts. This can materially affect both EBITDA and working capital calculations.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A target''s financial statements report ''exceptional items'' of €18M, primarily relating to ''restructuring initiatives.'' How should a PE buyer evaluate these?', '["Automatically exclude them from EBITDA as one-time","Examine whether the items are genuinely non-recurring or represent a recurring pattern that should be built into the normalised cost base; legitimate exceptional items are truly one-off, not annual restructuring","Always include them in EBITDA","Double them to show conservatism"]'::jsonb, 1, '''Exceptional'' or ''non-recurring'' items are often legitimate one-off costs (severance for a plant closure, settlement of specific litigation, asset impairments) that distort underlying performance. But ''exceptional items'' that appear every year — annual restructuring, recurring legal settlements, perpetual integration costs — are simply part of the business and shouldn''t be excluded. PE buyers trace these items back 3-5 years to test whether they''re truly non-recurring.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A conglomerate target''s income statement shows results from both ''continuing operations'' and ''discontinued operations.'' What does this distinction mean for PE analysis?', '["Both sets of results are equally important","Continuing operations represent the ongoing business; discontinued operations represent a subsidiary or segment being divested or already sold — only continuing operations are relevant to the target''s future","Discontinued operations indicate legal problems","The distinction is arbitrary"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Under IFRS 5 / ASC 205-20, businesses being divested or already disposed of are reported separately as ''discontinued operations.'' This isolates their results from the ongoing business. For PE analysis, only continuing operations matter when evaluating future performance potential. However, the buyer should understand why a segment was discontinued (poor performance? strategic pivot? regulatory forced?) and whether it reveals insights about management decision-making.'),
  ('68cca497-8e72-4064-9781-f387f05c8492', 'financial-analysis-statements', 'A PE buyer reviewing a target''s statements notices that ''interest expense'' appears separate from ''operating income'' on the P&L. Why is interest expense kept below operating income?', '["It''s an accounting error","Interest expense reflects financing structure, not operational performance — separating it allows comparison of operational results across companies with different debt levels","Interest expense is optional to include","Interest expense is always excluded from financial statements"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Operating income measures the company''s ability to generate profits from core operations. Interest expense is a financing cost, not an operating cost — two companies with identical operations but different debt levels would show different interest. Keeping interest below operating income allows cross-company comparison of operational performance independent of capital structure. For PE analysis, EBITDA (which excludes interest) is even more useful for this reason.')
